from China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative?. (No. 2019-32. HKUST Institute for Emerging Market Studies, 2019) [https://iems.ust.hk/assets/publications/thought-leadership-briefs/tlb32/park-which-countries-benefited-bri-hkustiems-tlb32.pdf online].\n* Scissors, Derek. \"The Belt and Road is Overhyped, Commercially.\" ''AEI Paper & Studies''  (American Enterprise Institute, 2019) [https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A593351967/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=278b77e2 online]\n* Shah, Abdur Rehman. \"China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative: The Way to the Modern Silk Road and the Perils of Overdependence.\" ''Asian Survey'' 59.3 (2019): 407-428. DOI: 10.1525/as.2019.59.3.407\n* Tjia, Yin-nor Linda. \"The Unintended Consequences of Politicization of the Belt and Road\u2019s China-Europe Freight Train Initiative.\" ''The China Journal'' 83.1 (2020): 58-78 https://doi.org/10.1086/706743 \n* Winter, Tim. \"Geocultural Power: China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative.\" ''Geopolitics'' (2020): 1-24. https://doi.org/10.1080/14650045.2020.1718656\n* [[World Pensions & Investments Forum|World Pensions Council (WPC)]] policy paper: [https://www.fnlondon.com/articles/chinese-revolution-could-lure-overseas-investment-nicholas-firzli-20151012 Chinese Revolution Could Lure Overseas Investment], Dow Jones Financial News, 12 October 2015\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/13/business/china-railway-one-belt-one-road-1-trillion-plan.html ''The New York Times'' \u2013 \"Behind China's $1 Trillion Plan\"], 13 May 2017\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|One Belt, One Road}}\n* [http://english.gov.cn/beltAndRoad/ Official website by State Council]\n* [https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/ Official website by Office of the Leading Group for the Belt and Road Initiative]\n* [http://www.beltandroad.gov.hk/ Belt and Road Initiative \u2013 Hong Kong]\n* [http://multimedia.scmp.com/news/china/article/One-Belt-One-Road/index.html Belt and Road Initiative \u2013 ''South China Morning Post'']\n\n{{One Belt, One Road}}\n{{Xi Jinping}}\n\n[[Category:Year of establishment missing]]\n[[Category:Foreign direct investment]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of China]]\n[[Category:Chinese economic policy]]\n[[Category:One Belt, One Road| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Development strategy and framework, proposed by China}}\n{{about|Chinese infrastructure projects in Asia, Europe, and Africa|the U.S. Initiative|New Silk Road Initiative}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date= November 2018}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Belt and Road Initiative\n| image = \n| image_border = \n| size = \n| caption = \n| mcaption = \n| abbreviation = \n| motto = \n| formation = {{start date and age|2013|df=yes}}<br>{{start date|2017|df=yes}} (Forum)\n| type = \n| status = \n| purpose = \"to construct a unified large market and make full use of both international and domestic markets, through cultural exchange and integration, to enhance mutual understanding and trust of member nations, ending up in an innovative pattern with capital inflows, talent pool, and technology database\"\n| headquarters = \n| location = [[China]]\n| region_served = [[Asia]]<br />[[Africa]]<br />[[Europe]]<br />[[Middle East]]<br />[[Americas]]\n| leader_title = Leader\n| leader_name = {{flagdeco|PRC}} [[Xi Jinping]] (2019)\n| main_organ = \n| affiliations = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| title = '''The Silk Road Economic Belt and the 21st-century Maritime Silk Road'''\n| order = st\n| s = {{linktext|\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def|\u7ecf\u6d4e|\u5e26|\u548c}}21{{linktext|\u4e16\u7eaa|\u6d77\u4e0a}}\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def\n| t = \u7d72\u7da2\u4e4b\u8def\u7d93\u6fdf\u5e36\u548c21\u4e16\u7d00\u6d77\u4e0a\u7d72\u7da2\u4e4b\u8def\n| p = S\u012bch\u00f3u zh\u012b l\u00f9 j\u012bngj\u00ecd\u00e0i h\u00e9 \u00e8rsh\u00edy\u012b sh\u00ecj\u00ec\n h\u01ceish\u00e0ng s\u012bch\u00f3u zh\u012b l\u00f9\n| j = si<sup>1</sup> cau<sup>4</sup> zi<sup>1</sup> lou<sup>6</sup> ging<sup>1</sup> zai<sup>3</sup> daai<sup>3</sup> wo<sup>4</sup> ji<sup>6</sup> sap<sup>6</sup> jat<sup>1</sup> sai<sup>3</sup> gei<sup>2</sup> hoi<sup>2</sup> soeng<sup>6</sup> si<sup>1</sup> cau<sup>4</sup> zi<sup>1</sup> lou<sup>6</sup>\n| poj = si-ti\u00fb-chi-lo\u0358 keng-ch\u00e8-t\u00e0i h\u00f4 j\u012b-si\u030dp-it s\u00e8-k\u00ed h\u00e1i-si\u014dng si-ti\u00fb-chi-lo\u0358\n| altname = One Belt, One Road (OBOR)\n| order2 = st\n| s2 = {{linktext|\u4e00\u5e26\u4e00\u8def}}\n| t2 = \u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\n| p2 = Y\u00edd\u00e0i y\u00edl\u00f9\n| j2 = jat<sup>1</sup> daai<sup>3</sup> jat<sup>1</sup> lou<sup>6</sup>\n| poj2 = It-t\u00e0i It-l\u014d\u0358\n| c = \n| mi = \n| ci = \n}}\n{{Politics of China |expanded = Foreign }}\nThe '''Belt and Road Initiative''' ('''BRI''', or '''B&R'''<ref>{{cite web |title=\u6211\u59d4\u7b49\u6709\u5173\u90e8\u95e8\u89c4\u8303\"\u4e00\u5e26\u4e00\u8def\"\u5021\u8bae\u82f1\u6587\u8bd1\u6cd5 |url=http://www.ndrc.gov.cn/gzdt/201509/t20150921_751695.html |website=www.ndrc.gov.cn |publisher=National Development and Reform Commission |language=zh-cn |accessdate=7 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511191431/http://www.ndrc.gov.cn:80/gzdt/201509/t20150921_751695.html |archivedate=5 May 2019 |date=11 May 2019}}</ref>) is a global development strategy adopted by the [[Government of China|Chinese government]] in 2013 involving infrastructure development and investments in nearly 70 countries and international organizations in [[Asia]], [[Europe]], and [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/regional-integration/brief/belt-and-road-initiative|title=Belt and Road Initiative|website=World Bank|language=en|access-date=10 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219015644/http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/regional-integration/brief/belt-and-road-initiative|archive-date=19 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beltandroadforum2019.com/conference-profile/overview/|title=Overview \u2013 Belt and Road Initiative Forum 2019|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n<!-- References should be used sparsely in the lead- they go in the body <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/panama-first-in-latin-america-to-join-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative/|title=Panama first in Latin America to join China's Belt and Road Initiative|date=7 December 2018|website=New Europe|language=en-US|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thefinancialexpress.com.bd/economy/global/152-countries-intl-organisations-sign-belt-and-road-deals-with-china-1551686061|title=152 countries, int'l organisations sign Belt and Road deals with China|last=Express|first=The Financial|website=The Financial Express|language=en|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref>-->\n\nThe [[paramount leader|leader]] of the [[China|People's Republic of China]], [[Xi Jinping]], originally announced the strategy during official visits to Indonesia and Kazakhstan in 2013.<!-- <ref>{{Cite journal|last= Imomnazar|first= Imomov|date=26 July 2018|title= Impact of \u00abOne Belt, One Road\u00bb initiatives to the economy of Central Asian countries|url= http://dx.doi.org/10.24052/ijbed/v06nu02/art-03|journal= International Journal of Business & Economic Development|volume= 06|issue= 02|doi= 10.24052/ijbed/v06nu02/art-03|issn= 2051-848X}}</ref>--> \"Belt\" refers to the [[Land transport|overland routes]] for [[Road transport|road]] and [[rail transport]]ation, called \"the ''Silk Road Economic Belt''\"; whereas \"road\" refers to the [[Maritime transport|sea routes]], or the [[21st Century Maritime Silk Road]].{{r|what}}\n\nFormerly known as '''One Belt One Road''' ('''OBOR''') ({{zh|s=\u4e00\u5e26\u4e00\u8def}}, short for the '''Silk Road Economic Belt and the 21st-century Maritime Silk Road''' ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5e26\u548c21\u4e16\u7eaa\u6d77\u4e0a\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def}})<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=22 March 2019|title=Wayback Machine|url=http://www.cbbc.org/cbbc/media/cbbc_media/One-Belt-One-Road-main-body.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713011420/http://www.cbbc.org/cbbc/media/cbbc_media/One-Belt-One-Road-main-body.pdf|archivedate=13 July 2017|date=13 July 2017}}</ref>), it has been referred to as the '''Belt and Road Initiative (BRI)''' since 2016 when the Chinese government considered the emphasis on the word \"one\" was prone to misinterpretation.<ref name=\"Latvia\" /> However, \"One Belt One Road\" ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u4e00\u5e26\u4e00\u8def}}) is still used in Chinese-language media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2019-08/18/c_1124890399.htm |language=zh-cn|script-title=zh:\u738b\u6bc5\uff1a\u7740\u529b\u6253\u9020\u897f\u90e8\u9646\u6d77\u65b0\u901a\u9053 \u63a8\u52a8\u9ad8\u8d28\u91cf\u5171\u5efa\"\u4e00\u5e26\u4e00\u8def\"-\u65b0\u534e\u7f51|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=21 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821145507/http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2019-08/18/c_1124890399.htm|archive-date=21 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese government calls the initiative \"a bid to enhance regional connectivity and embrace a brighter future\".{{r|\"centralGovernment\"}} Some observers see it as a push for Chinese dominance in global affairs with a China-centered trading network.{{r|comp1|comp2}} The project has a targeted completion date of 2049,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pr.com/press-release/780645|title=CrowdReviews Partnered with Strategic Marketing & Exhibitions to Announce: One Belt, One Road Forum|date=25 March 2019|website=PR.com|access-date=30 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430071306/https://www.pr.com/press-release/780645|archive-date=30 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which coincides with the 100th anniversary of the People's Republic of China.\n\n==History==\nThe initiative was unveiled by Chinese [[paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]] in September and October 2013 during visits to [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Indonesia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/04/20/content_281475092566326.htm|title=Chronology of China's Belt and Road Initiative|website=China's State Council|language=en|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923085510/http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/04/20/content_281475092566326.htm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and was thereafter promoted by [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] [[Li Keqiang]] during [[state visit]]s to [[Asia]] and [[Europe]]. The initiative was given intensive coverage by [[Media of China#Official media channels|Chinese state media]], and by 2016 often being featured in the ''[[People's Daily]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Qian |first1=Gang (\u94b1\u94a2) |url=http://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/3gj_W8D7dAecOH73gsRxoA |script-title=zh:\u94b1\u94a2\u8bed\u8c61\u62a5\u544a\uff1a\u515a\u5a92\u5173\u952e\u8bcd\u6e29\u5ea6\u6d4b\u8bd5 |publisher=[[WeChat]] |date=2017-02-23 |language=zh-cn}}{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227213916/https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/3gj_W8D7dAecOH73gsRxoA |date=27 February 2019 }}<!--\u5fae\u4fe1\u516c\u4f17\u53f7\u201c\u5c3d\u77e5\u5929\u4e0b\u4e8b\"--></ref>\n\nInitially, the initiative was termed One Belt One Road Strategy, but officials decided that the term \"strategy\" would create suspicions so they opted for the more inclusive term \"initiative\" in its translation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warontherocks.com/2019/03/jaw-jaw-the-geo-economic-challenge-of-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative/|title=The Geo-Economic Challenge of China's Belt and Road Initiative|last=Rolland|first=Nad\u00e8ge|date=5 March 2019|website=War on the Rocks|language=en-US|access-date=1 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701014926/https://warontherocks.com/2019/03/jaw-jaw-the-geo-economic-challenge-of-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative/|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Initial objectives===\nThe stated objectives are \"to construct a unified large market and make full use of both international and domestic markets, through [[cultural exchange]] and integration, to enhance mutual understanding and trust of member nations, ending up in an innovative pattern with capital inflows, [[talent pool]], and technology database.\"<ref name=\"uniview\">{{cite web |title=News\u2014Zhejiang Uniview Technologies Co., Ltd. |url=http://en.uniview.com/News/News/201809/804999_169683_0.htm |website=en.uniview.com |accessdate=11 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511095521/http://en.uniview.com/News/News/201809/804999_169683_0.htm |archive-date=11 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nThe initial focus has been infrastructure investment, education, construction materials, railway and highway, automobile, real estate, power grid, and iron and steel.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Belt and Road in Big Data 2016|last=General Office of Leading Group of Advancing the Building of the Belt and Road Initiative|date=2016|work=Beijing: the Commercial Press|access-date=}}</ref> Already, some estimates list the Belt and Road Initiative as one of the largest infrastructure and investment projects in history, covering more than 68 countries, including 65% of the [[World population|world's population]] and 40% of the global [[gross domestic product]] as of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4776845/china-xi-jinping-belt-road-initiative-obor/|title=What to Know About China's Belt and Road Initiative Summit|website=Time|language=en|access-date=30 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128230549/http://time.com/4776845/china-xi-jinping-belt-road-initiative-obor/|archive-date=28 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/05/11/asia/china-one-belt-one-road-explainer/index.html|title=Just what is this One Belt, One Road thing anyway?|first=James |last=Griffiths|work=CNN|access-date=30 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130145534/https://www.cnn.com/2017/05/11/asia/china-one-belt-one-road-explainer/index.html|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Belt and Road Initiative addresses an \"infrastructure gap\" and thus has potential to accelerate economic growth across the [[Asia Pacific]] area, [[Africa]] and [[Central and Eastern Europe]]: a report from the [[World Pensions & Investments Forum|World Pensions Council (WPC)]] estimates that Asia, excluding China, requires up to US$900 billion of infrastructure investments per year over the next decade, mostly in debt instruments, 50% above current infrastructure spending rates.<ref name=\"World Bank blog\">{{cite news|first1=Nicolas|last1=[[World Pensions & Investments Forum|3=World Pensions Council (WPC)]] Firzli|title=World Pensions Council: Pension Investment in Infrastructure Debt: A New Source of Capital|url=http://blogs.worldbank.org/ppps/pension-investment-infrastructure-debt-new-source-capital-project-finance/|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=World Bank blog|date=February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606060630/https://blogs.worldbank.org/ppps/pension-investment-infrastructure-debt-new-source-capital-project-finance|archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The gaping need for long term capital explains why many Asian and Eastern European heads of state \"gladly expressed their interest to join this new international financial institution focusing solely on 'real assets' and infrastructure-driven economic growth\".<ref name=\"Analyse Financi\u00e8re\">{{cite news |first1=M. Nicolas J. |last1=[[World Pensions & Investments Forum|3=World Pensions Council (WPC)]] Firzli |title=China's Asian Infrastructure Bank and the 'New Great Game' |url=https://www.academia.edu/19535167 |accessdate=5 February 2016 |work=Analyse Financi\u00e8re |date=October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129073111/http://www.academia.edu/19535167/China_s_AIIB_America_s_Pivot_to_Asia_and_the_Geopolitics_of_Infrastructure_Investments |archive-date=29 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Political control==\nThe Leading Group for advancing the Development of One Belt One Road was formed sometime in late 2014, and its leadership line-up publicized on 1 February 2015. This steering committee reports directly into the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China]] and is composed of several political heavyweights, evidence of the importance of the program to the government. Then Vice-Premier [[Zhang Gaoli]], who was also a member of the 7-man [[Politburo Standing Committee]] then, was named leader of the group, with [[Wang Huning]], [[Wang Yang (politician)|Wang Yang]], [[Yang Jing]], and [[Yang Jiechi]] being named deputy leaders.<ref name=\"Feng\">{{cite news|url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20150405/43488218_0.shtml |script-title=zh:\u4e00\u5e26\u4e00\u8def\u9886\u5bfc\u73ed\u5b50\"\u4e00\u6b63\u56db\u526f\"\u540d\u5355\u9996\u66dd\u5149|date=5 April 2015|work=Ifeng| language = zh-hans|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223044614/http://news.ifeng.com/a/20150405/43488218_0.shtml|archive-date=23 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, Chinese Premier [[Li Keqiang]] called for accelerating the Belt and Road Initiative along with the [[BCIM Forum#BCIM Economic Corridor|Bangladesh\u2013China\u2013India\u2013Myanmar Economic Corridor]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Joshi|first=Prateek|date=2016|title=The Chinese Silk Road in South & Southeast Asia: Enter \"Counter Geopolitics\"|url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0168-ssoar-52348-4|journal=IndraStra Global|language=en|issue=3|page=4|doi=10.6084/m9.figshare.3084253|type=Data Set}}</ref> and the [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor]] in his government work report presented to the annual meeting of the country's legislature.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn 28 March 2015, [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|China's State Council]] outlined the principles, framework, key areas of cooperation and cooperation mechanisms with regard to the initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.ndrc.gov.cn/newsrelease/201503/t20150330_669367.html|title=Vision and Actions on Jointly Building Silk Road Economic Belt and 21st-Century Maritime Silk Road|date=28 March 2015|work=National Development and Reform Commission (NDRC), People's Republic of China|access-date=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127225143/http://en.ndrc.gov.cn/newsrelease/201503/t20150330_669367.html|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure networks==\nThe Belt and Road Initiative is about improving the physical infrastructure along land corridors that roughly equate to the old [[silk road]]. These are the belts in the title, and a maritime silk road.<ref name=\"UnitedNations\" /> Infrastructure corridors encompassing around 60 countries, primarily in Asia and Europe but also including [[Oceania]] and [[East Africa]], will cost an estimated US$4\u20138 trillion.<ref name=\"ejinsight20160412\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ejinsight.com/20160412-getting-lost-one-belt-one-road/|title=Getting lost in 'One Belt, One Road'|date=12 April 2016|access-date=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414014511/http://www.ejinsight.com/20160412-getting-lost-one-belt-one-road/|archive-date=14 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Econ27\">[https://www.economist.com/news/china/21701505-chinas-foreign-policy-could-reshape-good-part-world-economy-our-bulldozers-our-rules Our bulldozers, our rules] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223090241/https://www.economist.com/news/china/21701505-chinas-foreign-policy-could-reshape-good-part-world-economy-our-bulldozers-our-rules |date=23 December 2017 }}, The Economist, 2 July 2016</ref> The initiative has been contrasted with the two US-centric trading arrangements, the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] and the [[Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership]].<ref name=Econ27/> The projects receive financial support from the Silk Road Fund and [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] while they are technically coordinated by the [[B&R Summit Forum]].\nThe land corridors include:<ref name=\"UnitedNations\" />\n* The [[New Eurasian Land Bridge]], which runs from [[Western China]] to [[European Russia|Western Russia]] through Kazakhstan, and includes the [[Chongqing-Xinjiang-Europe Railway|Silk Road Railway]] through China's [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Autonomous Region]], [[Kazakhstan]], Russia, [[Belarus]], Poland and Germany.\n* The [[China\u2013Mongolia\u2013Russia Corridor]], which will run from Northern China to the [[Russian Far East]]. The Russian government-established [[Russian Direct Investment Fund]] and China's [[China Investment Corporation]], a Chinese government investment agency, partnered in 2012 to create the Sino-Russian Investment Fund, which concentrates on opportunities in bilateral integration.<ref name=\"rcif\">{{cite news|title=China to step up Russian debt financing|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2015xiattendwwii/2015-05/09/content_20666880.htm|newspaper=China Daily|date=9 May 2015|access-date=23 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723122617/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2015xiattendwwii/2015-05/09/content_20666880.htm|archive-date=23 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://china.org.cn/business/node_7207419.htm|title=Silk Road Economic Belt_China.org.cn|website=china.org.cn|access-date=23 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315201700/http://www.china.org.cn/business/node_7207419.htm|archive-date=15 March 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n* The [[China\u2013Central Asia\u2013West Asia Corridor]], which will run from Western China to Turkey.\n* The [[China\u2013Indochina Peninsula Corridor]], which will run from Southern China to Singapore.\n* The [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor]] (CPEC) <small>({{zh|s=\u4e2d\u56fd-\u5df4\u57fa\u65af\u5766\u7ecf\u6d4e\u8d70\u5eca}}; {{lang-ur|{{nq|\u067e\u0627\u0643\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646-\u0686\u06cc\u0646 \u0627\u0642\u062a\u0635\u0627\u062f\u06cc \u0631\u0627\u06c1\u062f\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}}}</small>) which is also classified as \"closely related to the Belt and Road Initiative\",<ref name=\"vision\" /> a US$62 billion collection of infrastructure projects throughout [[Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1381733/cpec-investment-pushed-55b-62b/|title=CPEC investment pushed from $55b to $62b \u2013 The Express Tribune|date=12 April 2017|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170515011718/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1381733/cpec-investment-pushed-55b-62b/|archive-date=15 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"mcclatchydc\">{{cite news |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/world/article24783286.html |title=China's Xi in Pakistan to cement huge infrastructure projects, submarine sales |first1=Tom |last1=Hussain |newspaper=[[McClatchy News]] |date=19 April 2015 |location=Islamabad |accessdate=16 May 2017 |publisher=mcclatchydc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802124323/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/world/article24783286.html |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Kiani\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1287040|title=With a new Chinese loan, CPEC is now worth $57bn|work=Dawn|date=30 September 2016|accessdate=19 November 2016|first=Khaleeq|last=Kiani|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120084540/http://www.dawn.com/news/1287040|archive-date=20 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> which aims to rapidly modernize Pakistan's transportation networks, energy infrastructure, and economy.<ref name=\"mcclatchydc\" /><ref name=\"Kiani\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://herald.dawn.com/news/1153597/cpec-the-devil-is-not-in-the-details|title=CPEC: The devil is not in the details|date=23 November 2016|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514142904/http://herald.dawn.com/news/1153597/cpec-the-devil-is-not-in-the-details|archive-date=14 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/846370/economic-corridor-chinese-official-sets-record-straight/|title=Economic corridor: Chinese official sets record straight|date=2 March 2015|newspaper=[[The Express Tribune]]|access-date=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802204549/https://tribune.com.pk/story/846370/economic-corridor-chinese-official-sets-record-straight/|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 November 2016, CPEC became partly operational when Chinese cargo was transported overland to [[Gwadar Port]] for onward maritime shipment to [[Africa]] and [[West Asia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/cpec-takes-step-forward-violence-surges-balochistan/?platform=hootsuite|title=CPEC takes a step forward as violence surges in Balochistan|last=Ramachandran|first=Sudha|date=16 November 2016|website=www.atimes.com|access-date=19 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708080115/http://www.atimes.com/cpec-takes-step-forward-violence-surges-balochistan/?platform=hootsuite|archive-date=8 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Silk Road Economic Belt===\n[[File:One Belt One Road.png|thumb|upright=1.8|The Belt and Road Economies from its initial plan<ref>Based on {{lang|zh-Hant|\u300a\u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\u898f\u5283\u85cd\u5716\u300b}} in ''Nanfang Daily''</ref>]]\n[[Xi Jinping]] visited [[Astana|Astana, Kazakhstan]], and [[Southeast Asia]] in September and October 2013, and proposed jointly building a new economic area, the Silk Road Economic Belt ({{zh|s=\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5e26|t=}})<ref name=\"Xiat\">{{cite news|title=Xi Jinping Calls For Regional Cooperation Via New Silk Road|url=https://astanatimes.com/2013/09/xi-jinping-calls-for-regional-cooperation-via-new-silk-road/|agency=The Astana Times|access-date=31 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107055555/https://astanatimes.com/2013/09/xi-jinping-calls-for-regional-cooperation-via-new-silk-road/|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Essentially, the \"belt\" includes countries situated on the original [[Silk Road]] through Central Asia, [[West Asia]], the Middle East, and [[Europe]].<ref name=\":2\"/> The initiative would create a cohesive economic area by building both hard infrastructure such as rail and road links and soft infrastructure such as the trade agreements and a common commercial legal structure with a court system to police the agreements.{{r|what}}  It would increase cultural exchanges, and broadening trade. Outside this zone, which is largely analogous to the historical Silk Road, is an extension to include [[South Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]].\n\nMany of the countries that are part of this belt are also members of the China-led [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB). Three belts are proposed. The North belt would go through Central Asia and [[Russia]] to [[Europe]]. The Central belt passes through Central Asia and West Asia to the [[Persian Gulf]] and the Mediterranean. The South belt runs from [[China]] to Southeast Asia, South Asia, to the [[Indian Ocean]] through [[Pakistan]]. The strategy will integrate China with Central Asia through [[Kazakhstan]]'s [[Nurly Zhol]] infrastructure program.<ref name=\"EUreporterNZ\">{{cite news|title=Integrating #Kazakhstan Nurly Zhol, China's Silk Road economic belt will benefit all, officials say|url=https://www.eureporter.co/frontpage/2016/12/10/integrating-kazakhstan-nurly-zhol-chinas-silk-road-economic-belt-will-benefit-all-officials-say/|agency=EUReporter|access-date=14 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315090056/https://www.eureporter.co/frontpage/2016/12/10/integrating-kazakhstan-nurly-zhol-chinas-silk-road-economic-belt-will-benefit-all-officials-say/|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===21st Century Maritime Silk Road===\n{{Main|21st Century Maritime Silk Road}}\n\nThe \"21st Century Maritime Silk Road\" ({{zh|s=21\u4e16\u7eaa\u6d77\u4e0a\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def}}), or just the Maritime Silk Road, is the sea route 'corridor'.{{r|what}} It is a complementary initiative aimed at investing and fostering collaboration in Southeast Asia, Oceania, and Africa, through several contiguous bodies of water: the [[South China Sea]], the [[South Pacific Ocean]], and the wider [[Indian Ocean]] area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maritimesun.com/news/sri-lanka-supports-chinas-initiative-of-a-21st-century-maritime-silk-route|title=Sri Lanka Supports China's Initiative of a 21st Century Maritime Silk Route|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511193307/http://www.maritimesun.com/news/sri-lanka-supports-chinas-initiative-of-a-21st-century-maritime-silk-route|archivedate=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/09/china-pushes-maritime-silk-road-in-south-southeast-asia/|title=China Pushes 'Maritime Silk Road' in South, Southeast Asia|author=Shannon Tiezzi, The Diplomat|work=The Diplomat|access-date=16 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501173748/http://thediplomat.com/2014/09/china-pushes-maritime-silk-road-in-south-southeast-asia/|archive-date=1 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ciis7231376\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ciis.org.cn/english/2014-09/15/content_7231376.htm|title=Reflections on Maritime Partnership: Building the 21st Century Maritime Silk Road|access-date=16 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403001146/http://www.ciis.org.cn/english/2014-09/15/content_7231376.htm|archive-date=3 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was first proposed in October 2013 by [[Xi Jinping]] in a speech to the Indonesian Parliament.<ref name=\"chinadaily17008940\">{{cite web|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-10/04/content_17008940.htm|title=Xi in call for building of new 'maritime silk road'|work=China Daily|access-date=16 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302055647/http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-10/04/content_17008940.htm|archive-date=2 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Like the Silk Road Economic Belt initiative, most countries have joined the [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]].\n\n===Ice Silk Road===\nIn addition to the Maritime Silk Road, [[Russia]] and [[China]] are reported to have agreed jointly to build an 'Ice Silk Road' along the [[Northern Sea Route]] in the Arctic, along a maritime route which Russia considers to be part of its internal waters.<ref>Suokas, J., [https://gbtimes.com/china-russia-build-ice-silk-road-along-northern-sea-route China, Russia to build \u2018Ice Silk Road\u2019 along Northern Sea Route] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818233421/https://gbtimes.com/china-russia-build-ice-silk-road-along-northern-sea-route |date=18 August 2018 }}, GB Times, published 6 July 2017, accessed 10 March 2019</ref><ref name=\"Henderson\">{{Cite web|url=https://calrev.org/2019/07/18/cold-ambition-the-new-geopolitical-faultline/|title=Cold Ambition: The New Geopolitical Faultline|last=Henderson|first=Isaiah M.|date=18 July 2019|website=The California Review|language=en-US|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nChina [[COSCO]] Shipping Corp. has completed several trial trips on Arctic shipping routes, and Chinese and Russian companies are seeking cooperation on [[petroleum exploration in the Arctic|oil and gas exploration]] in the area and to advance comprehensive collaboration on infrastructure construction, tourism and scientific expeditions.<ref name=\"Henderson\"/>\n\nRussia together with China approached the practical discussion of the global infrastructure project Ice Silk Road. This was stated by representatives of [[Vnesheconombank|VnesheconomBank]] at the International conference Development of the shelf of Russia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.myseldon.com/en/news/index/206630988|title=The XVI International conference \"Development of a Shelf Russian Federation and CIS-2019\" will open on May 17, 2019 in Moscow|website=news.myseldon.com|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> and the CIS\u200a\u2014\u200a2019 (Petroleum Offshore of Russia), held in Moscow.\n\nThe delegates of the conference were representatives of the leadership of Russian and corporations ([[Gazprom]], [[Lukoil]], [[Rosatom|RosAtom]], Rosgeologiya, [[Vnesheconombank|VnesheconomBank]], Morneftegazproekt, Murmanshelf, Russian Helicopters, etc.), as well as foreign auditors ([[Deloitte]], member of the world Big Four) and consulting centers (Norwegian Rystad Energy and others.).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@victor.s.samoylov/russia-and-china-started-global-infrastructure-project-ice-silk-road-17298ba802bd|title=Russia and China started global infrastructure project Ice Silk Road|last=Pattinson|first=Victor|date=22 May 2019|website=Medium|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Super grid===\nThe [[Asian Super Grid|super grid]] project aims to develop six ultra high voltage electricity grids across China, north-east Asia, Southeast Asia, south Asia, central Asia and west Asia. The wind power resources of central Asia would form one component of this grid.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/e808a542-d6c6-11e7-8c9a-d9c0a5c8d5c9 |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202070611/https://www.ft.com/content/e808a542-d6c6-11e7-8c9a-d9c0a5c8d5c9 |archive-date=2 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Fairley |first1=Peter |title=China's Ambitious Plan to Build the World's Biggest Supergrid |url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/energy/the-smarter-grid/chinas-ambitious-plan-to-build-the-worlds-biggest-supergrid |website=IEEE Spectrum: Technology, Engineering, and Science News |accessdate=11 May 2019 |language=en |date=21 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512092508/https://spectrum.ieee.org/energy/the-smarter-grid/chinas-ambitious-plan-to-build-the-worlds-biggest-supergrid |archive-date=12 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Former===\n[[BCIM Forum|The Bangladesh\u2013China\u2013India\u2013Myanmar (BCIM) Economic Corridor]], which runs from southern China to Myanmar and was initially officially classified as \"closely related to the Belt and Road Initiative\".<ref name=\"vision\" /> Since the 2nd Belt and Road Forum in 2019, BCIM has been dropped from the list of covered projects due to India's refusal to participate in the Belt and Road Initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/china-drops-bcim-from-bri-projects-list-119042800540_1.html|title=China drops BCIM from BRI projects' list|date=28 April 2019|via=Business Standard|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref>\n\n== Project achievement ==\n[[File:Belt and Road Initiative participant map.svg|thumb|300px|Countries which signed cooperation documents related to the Belt and Road Initiative]]\nChina has signed cooperational document on the belt and road initiative with 138 countries and 30 international organisations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/info/iList.jsp?tm_id=126&cat_id=10122&info_id=77298|script-title=zh:\u5df2\u540c\u4e2d\u570b\u7c3d\u8a02\u5171\u5efa\u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\u5408\u4f5c\u6587\u4ef6\u7684\u570b\u5bb6\u4e00\u89bd|website=BRI Official Website|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=24 April 2019}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In terms of infrastructure construction, China and the countries along the Belt and Road have carried out effective cooperation in ports, railways, highways, power stations, aviation and telecommunications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/69500.htm|title=B&R interconnection witnesses great breakthroughs in 5-year development-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=19 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119174859/https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/69500.htm|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<br>BRI by Country, $ billion 2014-2018\n<br>\n<br>''Construction    \u2014       Investment''\n<br>1. Pakistan     31.9  \u2014  Singapore            24.3\n<br>2. Nigeria      23.2  \u2014  Malaysia             14.1\n<br>3. Bangladesh   17.5  \u2014  Russian Federation   10.4\n<br>4. Indonesia    16.8  \u2014  Indonesia             9.4\n<br>5. Malaysia     15.8  \u2014  South Korea           8.1\n<br>6. Egypt        15.3  \u2014  Israel                7.9\n<br>7. UAE          14.7  \u2014  Pakistan              7.6\n<br>''Source'' <ref>China Global Investment Tracker\nThe BRI's Future in Derek Scissors, \"The Belt and Road is Overhyped, Commercially.\" ''AEI Paper & Studies'' (American Enterprise Institute, 2019)  [https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A593351967/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=278b77e2 online]</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n\n====Djibouti====\n[[Djibouti]]'s [[Port of Doraleh|Doraleh Multi-purpose Port]] and the Hassan Gouled Aptidon international airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2018/09/02/belt-and-road-initiative-strikes-again-djibouti-risks-chinese-takeover-with-massive-loans-us-warns/|title=Belt and Road Initiative strikes again\u2026 Djibouti risks Chinese takeover with massive loans \u2013 US warns|date=2 September 2018|website=Kaieteur News|language=en-US|access-date=17 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119125522/https://www.kaieteurnewsonline.com/2018/09/02/belt-and-road-initiative-strikes-again-djibouti-risks-chinese-takeover-with-massive-loans-us-warns/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beltandroad.news/2019/04/29/how-tiny-african-nation-of-djibouti-became-linchpin-in-belt-road/|title=How tiny African Nation of Djibouti became Linchpin in Belt & Road|date=29 April 2019|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112192951/https://www.beltandroad.news/2019/04/29/how-tiny-african-nation-of-djibouti-became-linchpin-in-belt-road/|archive-date=12 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Djibouti, a remote country at the Horn of Africa, is at the heart of China's multibillion-dollar \"Belt and Road Initiative\", supporting Beijing's juggling of commercial and military objectives amid Western suspicions about its motives.\n\n====Egypt====\n[[Egypt]]'s [[New Administrative Capital of Egypt|New Administrative Capital]] is a landmark for the Belt and Road Initiative.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-03/18/c_137902708.htm|title=Feature: Chinese construction projects in Egypt's new capital city model for BRI-based cooperation|date=18 March 2019|access-date=2 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320230316/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-03/18/c_137902708.htm|archive-date=20 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Ethiopia====\n[[Ethiopia]]'s Eastern Industrial Zone is a manufacturing hub outside [[Addis Ababa]] that was built by China and occupied by factories of Chinese manufacturers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d6b444d35677a4d/share_p.html|title=Chinese Company Investing in Ethiopia's Eastern Industrial Zone|work=CGTN|date=15 May 2017|access-date=11 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011214503/https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d6b444d35677a4d/share_p.html|archive-date=11 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Chinese media and the vice director of the industrial zone, there were 83 companies resident within the zone, of which 56 had started production.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-06/11/c_137246794.htm|title=Ethiopia's First Industry Zone to Start Phase-2 Construction Soon|work=Xinhua Net|date=11 June 2018|access-date=11 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614032847/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-06/11/c_137246794.htm|archive-date=14 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> However, a study in ''[[Geoforum]]'' noted that the EIZ has yet to serve as a catalyst for [[Economy of Ethiopia|Ethiopia's overall economic development]] due to many factors including poor infrastructure outside the zone. Discrepancies between the two countries' industries also mean that Ethiopia cannot benefit from direct [[Technology transfer|technological transfer]] and innovation.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The eastern industrial zone in Ethiopia: Catalyst for development?|journal=Geoforum|volume=88|pages=28\u201335|authors=Philip Giannecchini, Ian Taylor|doi=10.1016/j.geoforum.2017.11.003|year=2018|hdl=10023/18971}}</ref>\n\nFrom October 2011 to February 2012, Chinese companies were contracted to supersede the century-old Ethio-Djibouti Railways by constructing a new electric standard gauge [[Addis Ababa\u2013Djibouti Railway]]. The new railway line, stretching more than {{Convert|750|km|}} and travelling at {{Convert|120|km/h||abbr=on}}, shortens the journey time between [[Addis Ababa]] and [[Djibouti (city)|Dijbouti]] from three days to about 12 hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37562177|title=Ethiopia-Djibouti electric railway line opens|date=5 October 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923125412/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37562177|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The first freight service began in November 2015 and passenger service followed in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.railway-technology.com/projects/ethiopia-djibouti-railway-line-modernisation/|title=Ethiopia-Djibouti Railway Line Modernization|work=Railway Technology|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118073817/https://www.railway-technology.com/projects/ethiopia-djibouti-railway-line-modernisation/|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On China\u2013Ethiopia cooperation on international affairs, China's Foreign Minister Wang Yi said that China and Ethiopia are both developing countries, and both countries are faced with a complicated international environment. He stated that the partnership will be a model at the forefront of developing China\u2013Africa relations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.beltandroad.news/2019/01/05/chinese-fm-prioritises-three-areas-in-development-of-china-ethiopia-relations/|title=Chinese FM prioritises three areas in development of China \u2013 Ethiopia relations|date=5 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Kenya====\nIn May 2014, Premier [[Li Keqiang]] signed a cooperation agreement with the [[Kenya]]n government to build the [[Mombasa\u2013Nairobi Standard Gauge Railway]] connecting Mombasa to Nairobi. The railway cost US$3.2bn and was Kenya's biggest infrastructure project since independence. The railway was claimed to cut the journey time from Mombasa to Nairobi from 9 hours by bus or 12 hours on the previous railway to 4.5 hours. In May 2017, Kenyan President [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] called the 470&nbsp;km railway a new chapter that \"would begin to reshape the story of Kenya for the next 100 years\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-40092600|title=Kenya Opens Nairobi-Monbasa Madaraka Express Railway|date=31 May 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923125813/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-40092600|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Kenya Railways Corporation, the railway carried 1.3 million Kenyans with a 96.7% seat occupancy and 600,000 tons of cargo in its first year of operation. Chinese media claim that the railway line boosted the country's GDP by 1.5% and created 46,000 jobs for locals and trained 1,600 railway professionals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-06/01/c_137223294.htm/|title=One Year On: China-built Railway Revitalizes Regional Trade in Kenya|date=1 June 2018|work=Xinhua Net|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630063553/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-06/01/c_137223294.htm|archive-date=30 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Nigeria ====\nOn 12 January 2019, [[Nigeria]]'s first standard gauge railway, which has been successfully operated for 900 days, had no major accidents since its inception. With the successful completion of the railway construction by China Civil Engineering Construction Company (CCECC), the Abuja Kaduna train service began commercial operation on 27 July 2016. The Abuja-Kaduna Railway Line is one of the first standard railroad railway modernization projects (SGRMP) in Nigeria. This is the first part of the Lagos-Kano standard metrics project, which will connect the business centres of Nigeria with the economic activity centres of the northwestern part of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/77420.htm|title=Nigeria's first standard gauge railway marks 900 days of safe operation-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=15 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115184219/https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/77420.htm|archive-date=15 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a resolution of the Johannesburg Summit of the China-Africa Cooperation Forum in 2015, the Chinese government promised to provide satellite television to 10,000 African villages. It is reported that each of the 1,000 selected villages in Nigeria, the most populous country in Africa, will receive two sets of solar projection television systems and a set of solar 32-inch digital TV integrated terminal systems. A total of 20,000 Nigerian rural families will benefit from the project. Kpaduma, an underdeveloped rural community on the edge of the Nigerian capital of Abuja, is familiar with analog TV and has no chance to see the satellite TV channels enjoyed by people in Nigerian towns. The implementation of the project will create more jobs, 1,000 Nigerians in selected villages have received training on how to install, recharge and operate satellite TV systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/77422.htm|title=China launches digital TV project for 1,000 Nigerian villages-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=17 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117174335/https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/77422.htm|archive-date=17 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Sudan====\nIn [[Sudan]], China has helped the country to establish its own oil industry, and provided agricultural assistance for the cotton industry.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nFuture plans include developing railways, roads, ports, a nuclear power station, solar power farms and more dams for irrigation and electricity generation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/28/c_137424486.htm|title=Spotlight: Sudan expects to play bigger role in Belt and Road Initiative -- analysts - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=17 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121524/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/28/c_137424486.htm|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nFreight train services between China and Europe were initiated in March 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-38654176|title=All aboard the China-to-London freight train|date=18 January 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923165855/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-38654176|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The service's first freight route linked China to Tehran. The [[Yiwu\u2013London railway line|China\u2013Britain route]] was launched in January 2017<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jwebb/2017/01/03/the-new-silk-road-china-launches-beijing-london-freight-train-route/#64df4ee61f13|title=The New Silk Road: China Launches Beijing-London Freight Train Route|date=3 January 2017|work=Jonathan Webb|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923164157/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jwebb/2017/01/03/the-new-silk-road-china-launches-beijing-london-freight-train-route/#64df4ee61f13#64df4ee61f13|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 2018, the network had expanded to cover 48 Chinese cities and 42 European destinations, delivering goods between China and Europe. The 10,000th trip was completed on 26 August 2018 with the arrival of freight train X8044 in [[Wuhan|Wuhan, China]] from [[Hamburg|Hamburg, Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/27/c_137422376.htm|title=China\u2013European Freight Trains Make 10,000 Trips|date=27 August 2018|work=Xinhua Net|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827144458/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/27/c_137422376.htm|archive-date=27 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The network was further extended southward to [[Vietnam]] in March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-03/18/c_137047977.htm|title=China\u2013Europe Freight Train Service Extended Southwards to Vietnam|date=18 March 2018|work=Xinhua Net|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923124025/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-03/18/c_137047977.htm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Poland ====\n[[File:Andrzej Duda i Xi Jinping w 2016.jpg|thumb|[[Poland]]'s President [[Andrzej Duda]] and Xi Jinping wave to the crowd during the inauguration of the [[Yiwu\u2013London railway line|China Railway Express]] in Warsaw, 20 June 2016]]\nPoland was one of the first European countries to sign a Memorandum of Understanding with China about the BRI in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201905/28/WS5cec97dca3104842260be305.html|title=Poland looking to bolster trade with China under BRI - Chinadaily.com.cn|last1=Dong |first1=Zhicheng (\u8463\u5fd7\u6210)|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=4 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104094359/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201905/28/WS5cec97dca3104842260be305.html|archive-date=4 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Poland's President Duda said that he hope Poland will become a gateway to Europe for China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poland and China sign universal strategic partnership pact |url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/257974,Poland-and-China-sign-universal-strategic-partnership-pact |work=Radio Poland |date=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nThe foreign ministers of China and Greece signed a [[Memorandum of Understanding]] related to further cooperation under the Belt and Road initiative on 29 August 2018. [[COSCO]] revitalized and currently runs the [[Port of Piraeus]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Xinhua |url=https://gbtimes.com/greece-to-strengthen-cooperation-with-china-under-belt-and-road |title=Greece to strengthen cooperation with China under Belt and Road |publisher=gbtimes.com |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404003728/https://gbtimes.com/greece-to-strengthen-cooperation-with-china-under-belt-and-road |archive-date=4 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://calrev.org/2019/02/04/the-chinese-empire-rises-bri-emerges-as-tool-of-conquest-and-challenge-to-the-us-order/|title=The Chinese Empire Rises: BRI Emerges as Tool of Conquest and Challenge to the U.S. Order|last=Henderson|first=Isaiah M.|date=4 February 2019|website=The California Review|language=en-US|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=':Belt&Road'>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beltandroad.news/2019/11/12/china-and-greece-are-natural-partners-in-belt-road-initiative/|title=China and Greece are \"natural partners\" in Belt & Road Initiative - Belt & Road News|date=12 November 2019}}</ref> Both China and Greece see each other as natural allies in developing the Belt & Road\", President Xi said at the start of a state visit aimed at deepening cooperation with Greece across the board, adding his desire to \"keep the momentum going\" and \"reinforce\" bilateral relations\n\n==== Portugal ====\nDuring president [[Xi Jinping|Xi's]] visit to [[Lisbon]] in December 2018, the Southern European nation signed a Memorandum of Understanding with China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2176560/portugal-wavers-xi-jinping-presses-europe-belt-and-road|title=Portugal signs agreement with China on Belt and Road Initiative|date=5 December 2018|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=6 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106091526/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2176560/portugal-wavers-xi-jinping-presses-europe-belt-and-road|archive-date=6 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Italy====\nIn March 2019, Italy became the first G7 Nation to join China's Belt and Road Initiative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamestown.org/program/italy-joins-the-belt-and-road-initiative-context-interests-and-drivers/|title=Italy Joins the Belt and Road Initiative: Context, Interests, and Drivers|last=Cristiani|first=Dario|date=24 April 2019|website=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424202932/http://jamestown.org/program/italy-joins-the-belt-and-road-initiative-context-interests-and-drivers/|archive-date=24 April 2019|access-date=9 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"italy24033019\">{{cite news|url=http://theindependent.in/italy-becomes-first-g7-nation-to-join-chinas-belt-road-initiative/|title=Italy becomes first G7 nation to join China's 'Belt & Road Initiative|work=theindependent.in|date=24 March 2019|access-date=24 March 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324140841/http://theindependent.in/italy-becomes-first-g7-nation-to-join-chinas-belt-road-initiative/|archive-date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Austria ====\nDuring a visit of Chancellor [[Sebastian Kurz|Kurz]] to China in April 2019, a Memorandum of Understanding was signed on [[Austria|Austria's]] cooperation in the BRI project. According to Kurz, Austria \"support[s] the One Belt One Road initiative and [is] trying to forge a close economic cooperation [with China]. Austria has know-how and expertise to offer in many areas where China is looking for the same\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imfino.com/en/pages/news/what-does-the-belt-and-road-initiative-bri-mean-for-austria-and-the-region-of-central-east-and-southeast-europe-cesee-part-2/|title=\"What Does the Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) Mean for Austria and the Region of Central East and Southeast Europe (CESEE)?\" (Part 2)|website=imfino.com|language=en|access-date=4 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104095158/https://imfino.com/en/pages/news/what-does-the-belt-and-road-initiative-bri-mean-for-austria-and-the-region-of-central-east-and-southeast-europe-cesee-part-2/|archive-date=4 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Luxembourg====\nOn 27 March 2019, Luxembourg signed an agreement with China to cooperate on Belt and Road Initiative.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-27/luxembourg-signs-accord-with-china-on-belt-and-road-initiative |title=Are you a robot? |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610152234/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-27/luxembourg-signs-accord-with-china-on-belt-and-road-initiative |archive-date=10 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Switzerland====\nOn 29 April 2019, during his visit in Beijing, Swiss President [[Ueli Maurer]] signed a Memorandum of Understanding with China under the Belt and Road Initiative.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stephens |first=Thomas |url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/state-visit_swiss-president-strengthens-economic-ties-with-china-/44926898 |title=Swiss president strengthens economic ties with China - SWI |publisher=Swissinfo.ch |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511210232/http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/state-visit_swiss-president-strengthens-economic-ties-with-china-/44926898 |archive-date=11 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Caucasus===\n\n====Armenia====\nOn 4 April 2019, the President of Armenia [[Armen Sarkissian]] received a delegation led by Shen Yueyue, Vice-Chairwoman of the National People's Congress Standing Committee of China in [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]. President Sarkissian stated that Armenia and China are ancient countries with centuries-old tradition of cooperation since the existence of the Silk Road. The President noted the development of cooperation in the 21st century in the sidelines of the One Belt One Road program initiated by the top leadership of China and stated that \"It\u2019s time for Armenia to become part of the new Silk Road\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/970140.html|title=It's time for Armenia to become part of new Silk Road \u2013 Armenian President meets with Chinese delegation|website=armenpress.am|access-date=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406024606/https://armenpress.am/eng/news/970140.html|archive-date=6 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Azerbaijan====\nOn 25-27 April 2019, the Second [[Belt and Road Forum]] for International Cooperation was held in Beijing, China. A delegation led by President of the Republic of [[Azerbaijan]] [[Ilham Aliyev]] attended the Forum. The event brought together heads of governments from 37 countries, including Azerbaijan, Russia, Pakistan, Kazakhstan, Austria, Belarus, the Czech Republic, Greece, Hungary, Italy, Serbia, Singapore, the UAE, and others, as well as heads of international organizations. In his speech, the President Ilham Aliyev stated that, \u201cFrom the very beginning Azerbaijan supported the Belt and Road initiative put forward by President Xi Jinping. This initiative not only provides transportation of productivity, it strengthens ties between different countries, serve the course of dialogue and cooperation, creates new opportunities for international trade.\u201d \n\nThe creation of modern infrastructure is one of the priorities for Azerbaijan and will foster the flow of international trade by building bridges between Europe and Asia. Among these notable infrastructure projects are [[Baku-Tbilisi-Kars]] railway and the [[Baku International Sea Trade Port]] (the Port of Baku) that play an important role in transportation in [[Eurasia]]. Currently, the Port of Baku has the capacity to handle 15 million tons of cargo, including 100000 TEU, which will grow to 25 million tons of cargo and 500000 TEU in the future. By investing in modern transportation and logistics infrastructure Azerbaijan not only transforms itself into an important transportation hub but also contributes to the cooperation with countries involved in East-West and North-South Corridors.\n\n====Georgia====\nOn 25 April 2019, the Minister of Infrastructure and Regional Development of [[Georgia(country)|Georgia]] Maya Tskitishvili stated that, \"One Belt-One Road initiative is important for Georgia and the country is actively involved in its development.\" She also noted that Georgia was among the first countries who signed the memorandum for developing the 'One Belt-One Road' initiative in March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2019/1115 | title=Georgian Infrastructure Minister participating at Belt and Road Forum in China | access-date=2 October 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218203532/https://agenda.ge/en/news/2019/1115 | archive-date=18 December 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Russia and EEU===\n[[File:With participants of the Belt and Road international forum.jpg|thumb|Participants of the [[Belt and Road Forum]] in Beijing in 2017]]\n[[File:Map of Central Asia.png|thumb|250px|Central Asian Countries]]\nOn 26 April 2019, the leaders of [[Russia]] and China called their countries \"good friends\" and vowed to work together in pursuing greater economic integration of [[Eurasia]]. On the sidelines of the Belt and Road Forum in Beijing, Chinese President Xi Jinping and his Russian counterpart [[Vladimir Putin]] pledged to further strengthen economic and trade cooperation between the two sides. [[Vladimir Putin]] further stated that, \"countries gathering under the Belt and Road Initiative and the [[Eurasian Economic Union]] share long-term strategic interests of peace and growth\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3007883/china-and-russia-forge-stronger-eurasian-economic-ties |title=China and Russia forge stronger Eurasian economic ties as Vladimir Putin gets behind Xi Jinping's belt and road plan in face of US hostility &#124; South China Morning Post |publisher=Scmp.com |date=26 April 2019 |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527233215/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3007883/china-and-russia-forge-stronger-eurasian-economic-ties |archive-date=27 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn June 2019, Xi and Putin stated they were committed to the concept of building the \"Great Eurasian Partnership\". That took the form of Xi stating that he had agreed with Putin to link the Eurasian Economic Union with China's Belt & Road Initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tass.com/economy/1062688|publisher=[[TASS]]|title=China's leader: One Belt One Road and EAEU synergy to boost region's developmentl cooperation|date=7 June 2019|accessdate=17 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610052503/http://tass.com/economy/1062688|archive-date=10 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/world/2019-06/06/c_1124588552.htm|publisher=[[Xinhua]] |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u548c\u4fc4\u7f57\u65af\u8054\u90a6\u5173\u4e8e\u53d1\u5c55\u65b0\u65f6\u4ee3\u5168\u9762\u6218\u7565\u534f\u4f5c\u4f19\u4f34\u5173\u7cfb\u7684\u8054\u5408\u58f0\u660e\uff08\u5168\u6587\uff09|date=6 June 2019|accessdate=17 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015215823/http://www.xinhuanet.com/world/2019-06/06/c_1124588552.htm|archive-date=15 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[China\u2013Belarus Industrial Park]] is a {{Convert|91.5|km2||abbr=on}} [[special economic zone]] established in [[Smalyavichy District|Smolevichy]], [[Minsk]] in 2013. According to the park's chief administrator, 36 international companies have settled in the park as of August 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/11/c_137383743.htm|title=Interview: China\u2013Belarus Industrial Park propels Belarusian economy|work=Xinhua Net|access-date=29 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818211915/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/11/c_137383743.htm|archive-date=18 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Chinese media said the park will create 6,000 jobs and become a real city with 10,000 residents by 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2017-10/12/content_33154129.htm|title=China\u2013Belarus Industrial Park makes breakthrough in attracting investors|work=China Daily|access-date=29 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929114648/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2017-10/12/content_33154129.htm|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n==== Central Asia ====\nThe five countries of Central Asia \u2013 Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan \u2013 are an important part of the land route of the Belt and Road Initiative (BRI).<ref>Vakulchuk, Roman and Indra Overland (2019) \u201c[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329310641 China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative through the Lens of Central Asia]\u201d, in Fanny M. Cheung and Ying-yi Hong (eds) ''Regional Connection under the Belt and Road Initiative. The Prospects for Economic and Financial Cooperation''. London: Routledge, pp. 115\u2013133.</ref> The Central Asia Data-Gathering and Analysis Team has identified 261 BRI projects within Central Asian nations with a minimum investment totaling more than 136 million USD. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.osce-academy.net/upload/file/20_BRI_in_Central_Asia.pdf|title=BRI in Central Asia: Overview of Chinese Projects|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2019, Kazakhstan invested about $30 billion on infrastructure development, transport and logistics assets and competence as part of the Belt and Road Initiative. Due Kazakhstan's infrastructure modernization, The Western Europe \u2013 Western China intercontinental highway now connects Europe and China through Russia and Kazakhstan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kazakhstan has turned into 'competitive transit hub', Nazarbayev tells Belt and Road forum |url=https://astanatimes.com/2019/04/kazakhstan-has-turned-into-competitive-transit-hub-nazarbayev-tells-belt-and-road-forum/ |website=astanatimes.com |access-date=13 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214063028/https://astanatimes.com/2019/04/kazakhstan-has-turned-into-competitive-transit-hub-nazarbayev-tells-belt-and-road-forum/ |archive-date=14 December 2019 |url-status=live |date=27 April 2019 }}</ref> Kazakhstan stands to receive a potential $5 billion annually in transit fees from goods moving through it to other markets.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldbank.org/en/news/feature/2019/03/11/belt-and-road-initiative-in-central-asia-and-the-caucasus|title=Belt and Road Initiative in Central Asia and the Caucasus|date=March 11, 2019|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn Kyrgyzstan, 2011-2017 BRI projects total committed funds is equal to 4.1 billion USD. Employment created from established companies is not significant, making up only 0.1-0.3% of total employment in the country, just several thousand jobs. The weight of debt repayment for BRI projects will not be felt until the 2020s, because of the grace periods on most loans ranging from 5-11 years. Kyrgyzstan has the potential to benefit greatly from BRI; If tax legislation is handled well, particularly in manufacturing and transit projects, then revenue will be high.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mogilevskii|first=Roman|date=2019|title=Kyrgyzstan and the Belt and Road Initiative|url=https://www.uca.int/Content/Downloads/UCA-IPPA-WP50_Kyrgyzstan%20and%20Belt%20Road%20Initiative_ENG.pdf|journal=University of Central Asia Working Papers|volume=#50|pages=26|via=}}</ref> \n\n\u201cFrom the perspective of Uzbekistan, the BRI could help open the corridor to the Persian Gulf, enabling expansion of commercial and trade routes for the country.\u201d Exporting Uzbeks goods to more regions is a highly attractive incentive for Uzbekistan. At the First Belt and Road Forum held in Beijing May, 2017 both presidents, Mirziyoyev of Uzbekistan and Xi Jinping of China, spoke positively of future collaboration in BRI advancement. During those meetings, the \u201ctwo countries signed 115 deals worth more $23 billion on enhancing their cooperation in electrical power, oil production, chemicals, architecture, textiles, pharmaceutical engineering, transportation, infrastructure and agriculture.\u201d <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Qoraboyev|first=Ikboljon|date=April 2018|title=The Belt and Road Initiative and Uzbekistan's New Strategy of Development: Sustainability of mutual relevance and positive dynamics|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/324560481|journal=Research Gate|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2019 Uzbekistan establishment a new government group in charge of aligning their own country\u2019s development plan with China\u2019s BRI ambitions. China is Uzbekistan\u2019s largest trade partner (both in imports and exports) and has more than 1500 Chinese businesses within its territory. In 2018, \u201cChina-Uzbekistan trade surged 48.4 percent year-on-year, reaching 6.26 billion U.S. dollars.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/2019-10/31/content_75358846.htm|title=BRI cooperation boosts China-Uzbekistan partnership|date=October 31, 2019|work=China.org.cn|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\u201cBRI projects in Tajikistan range from roads and railways to pipelines and power plants, even including traffic cameras.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Sam|url=https://nationalinterest.org/feature/tajikistan-belt-and-road-paved-good-intentions-29607|title=For Tajikistan, the Belt and Road Is Paved with Good Intentions|date=August 23, 2018|work=The National Interest|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, \u201cTajikistan paid a Chinese company building a power plant with a gold mine; a few years earlier it swapped Beijing some land for debt.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bhutia|first=Sam|url=https://eurasianet.org/who-wins-in-chinas-great-central-asia-spending-spree|title=Who wins in China's great Central Asia spending spree?|date=October 2, 2019|work=Eurasianet|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTurkmenistan in most regards has been closed off to the world. However, Turkmenistan, because of a desire to see infrastructure and energy projects move ahead, is increasingly opening itself to the world. Turkmenistan doesn\u2019t have the capabilities of seeing many of its projects come to fruition on its own. In June 2016, Gurbanguly, Turkmenistan\u2019s president, approached Xi Jinping to discuss his desire to become more involved in BRI and seeing previously planned projects completed and or expanded. These projects include the Turkmenistan\u2019s and China gas pipeline (with four lines, the fourth forthcoming), [[International North\u2013South Transport Corridor|The International North-South transportation corridor]] (which provides railway connections between Russia, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan and Iran, with another line connecting China to Iran via Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan), [[Lapis Lazuli corridor|The Lapis Lazuli international transit corridor]] (rail connecting Afghanistan, Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey), and the [[Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline|Turkmenistan-Afghanistan- Pakistan-India (TAPI) pipeline]] project. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Choganov|first=Kerven|url=https://www.oboreurope.com/en/turkmenistan-strategic-corridors/]|title=Turkmenistan's strategic corridors|date=December 16, 2019|work=One Belt One Road Europe|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Hong Kong====\nDuring his 2016 [[Policy address of Hong Kong|policy address]], [[Hong Kong]] chief executive [[Leung Chun-ying]]'s announced his intention of setting up a Maritime Authority aimed at strengthening Hong Kong's maritime logistics in line with Beijing's economic policy.<ref name=\"ejinsight20151116\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ejinsight.com/20151116-lawmakers-should-stop-cy-leung-from-expanding-govt-power/|title=Lawmakers should stop CY Leung from expanding govt power|work=EJ Insight|date=16 November 2015|access-date=15 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223122948/http://www.ejinsight.com/20151116-lawmakers-should-stop-cy-leung-from-expanding-govt-power/|archive-date=23 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Leung mentioned \"One Belt, One Road\" no fewer than 48 times during the policy address,<ref name=\"scmp1901017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1901017/one-belt-one-road-gets-record-breaking-48-mentions-hong-kong|title=We get it, CY ... One Belt, One Road gets record-breaking 48 mentions in policy address|date=13 January 2016|work=South China Morning Post}}</ref> but details were scant.<ref name=\"now165175\">{{cite web|url=http://news.now.com/home/local/player?newsId=165175 |language=zh-Hant |script-title=zh:\u3010\u653f\u60c5\u3011\u88ab\u300c\u6d17\u7248\u300d\u7279\u9996\u8fa6\u5b98\u54e1\u8abf\u8077\u745e\u58eb|access-date=15 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117184118/http://news.now.com/home/local/player?newsId=165175|archive-date=17 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ejinsight20160114macro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ejinsight.com/20160114-2016-policy-address-too-macro-while-too-micro/|title=2016 Policy Address: too macro while too micro|work=EJ Insight|date=15 January 2016|access-date=15 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116231223/http://www.ejinsight.com/20160114-2016-policy-address-too-macro-while-too-micro/|archive-date=16 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Indonesia====\nIn 2016, [[China Railway]] International won a bid to build [[Indonesia]]'s first high-speed rail, the {{Convert|140|km||abbr=on}} [[High-speed rail in Indonesia#Jakarta\u2013Bandung\u2013Kertajati|Jakarta\u2013Bandung High Speed Rail]]. It will shorten the journey time between [[Jakarta]] and [[Bandung]] from over three hours to forty minutes<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-06/29/c_137290654.htm/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629232531/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-06/29/c_137290654.htm/|archive-date=29 June 2018|title=Construction of Jakarta-Bandung high-speed railway in full swing in Indonesia|work=Xinhua Net|access-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The project, initially scheduled for completion in 2019, was delayed by land clearance issues.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/02/19/jakarta-bandung-railway-project-wont-meet-target-minister.html|title=Jakarta-Bandung railway project won't meet target, Minister|work=The Jakarta Post|access-date=29 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929155850/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/02/19/jakarta-bandung-railway-project-wont-meet-target-minister.html|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> 2000 locals are working on the project.\n\n====Laos====\nIn [[Laos]], construction of the {{Convert|414|km||abbr=on}} [[Vientiane\u2013Boten Railway]] began on 25 December 2016 and is scheduled to be completed in 2021. It is China's first overseas railway project that will connect to China's railway network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-09/22/c_137486428.htm|title=China\u2013Laos railway completes first continuous beam block construction on Mekong River|work=Xinhua Net|date=22 September 2018|access-date=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017123559/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-09/22/c_137486428.htm|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Once operational, the Laos\u2013China Railway will be Laos' longest and connect with Thailand to become part of the proposed [[Kunming\u2013Singapore railway]], extending from the Chinese city of [[Kunming]] and running through Thailand and Laos to terminate at [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2015/11/china-laos-to-build-6-billion-railway-by-2020/|title=China, Laos to build $6 Billion Railway by 2020|work=The Diplomat|date=16 November 2015|access-date=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017163055/https://thediplomat.com/2015/11/china-laos-to-build-6-billion-railway-by-2020/|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/laos/10572583/Chinas-120mph-railway-arriving-in-Laos.html|title=China's 120mph railway arriving in Laos|work=The Telegraph|date=14 January 2014|access-date=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017123631/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/laos/10572583/Chinas-120mph-railway-arriving-in-Laos.html|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It is estimated to cost US$5.95 billion with 70% of the railway owned by China, while Laos's remaining 30% stake will be mostly financed by loans from China.<ref name=\"nikkei.com\">{{cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/Land-locked-Laos-on-track-for-controversial-China-rail-link|title=Land-locked Laos on track for controversial China rail link|date=24 July 2017|access-date=18 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018082654/https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/Land-locked-Laos-on-track-for-controversial-China-rail-link|archive-date=18 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> However, it faces opposition within Laos due to the high cost of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/08/china-thailand-rail-project-new-movement-old-problems|title=China-Thailand Rail Project: New Movement, Old Problems?|work=The Diplomat|date=29 August 2017|access-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016125914/https://thediplomat.com/2017/08/china-thailand-rail-project-new-movement-old-problems|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Maldives====\nMaldives undertook a number of China funded projects under the Presidency of Abdullah Yameen (2013\u201318), including the China Maldives Friendship Bridge, The Velana International Airport and the artificial island of Hulhulmale. Many of these investments were made without adequate disclosures to the public on their cost and other terms. Under President Yameen, Maldives also amended its constitution to allow foreigners to own land in the archipelago - following which the island of Feydhoo Finholu was taken up on a long term lease by a Chinese company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gatewayhouse.in/chinese-investments-in-the-maldives/|title=The Maldives: Investments Undermine Democracy|date=7 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Malaysia====\nUnder the [[Premiership of Najib Razak]], [[Malaysia]] signed multiple investment deals with China, including a US$27 billion [[MRL East Coast Rail Link|East Coast Rail Link]] project, pipeline projects worth more than $3.1 billion, as well as a $100 billion Forest City in [[Johor Bahru|Johor]].<ref>{{cite news |author1=Pooja Thakur Mahrotri |author2=En Han Choong |title=$100 Billion Chinese-Made City Near Singapore 'Scares the Hell Out of Everybody' |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2016-11-21/-100-billion-chinese-made-city-near-singapore-scares-the-hell-out-of-everybody |accessdate=16 October 2018 |work=Bloomberg |date=22 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016131433/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2016-11-21/-100-billion-chinese-made-city-near-singapore-scares-the-hell-out-of-everybody |archive-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> During the [[Malaysian general election, 2018|2018 Malaysian general election]], then-opposition leader [[Mahathir Mohamad]] expressed [[debt-trap diplomacy|disapproval of Chinese investment in Malaysia]], comparing it to selling off the country to foreigners.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shukry |first1=Anisah |last2=Ho |first2=Yudith |title=Malaysia's Mahathir Pledges to Review China Investment if Re-Elected |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-08/mahathir-pledges-to-review-china-investment-after-malaysia-vote |accessdate=16 October 2018 |work=Bloomberg |date=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823105726/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-08/mahathir-pledges-to-review-china-investment-after-malaysia-vote |archive-date=23 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Upon election as [[Prime Minister of Malaysia]], Mahathir labelled the China-funded projects as \"unfair\" deals authorized by former prime minister [[Najib Razak]] and would leave Malaysia \"indebted\" to [[China]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-21/mahathir-says-china-will-sympathise-with-malaysia-problems/10145750|title=Malaysia's Mahathir warns against 'new colonialism' during China visit|date=21 August 2018|work=ABC News|access-date=23 August 2018|language=en-AU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822083854/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-21/mahathir-says-china-will-sympathise-with-malaysia-problems/10145750|archive-date=22 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As was argued by [[Kit Wei Zheng]] of Citibank, he believed that the projects were likely to have been driven more by China's geolpolitical interests than by the profit motive<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/07/06/investments-from-china-wont-necessarily-benefit-malaysia/|title='Investments from China won't necessarily benefit Malaysia'|last=Reporters|first=F. M. T.|date=2017-07-06|website=Free Malaysia Today|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>.\n\nIn August 2018, at the end of an official visit to China, Mahathir cancelled the East Coast Rail Link project and two other pipeline projects that had been awarded to the [[China Petroleum Pipeline Bureau]]. These had been linked to [[1Malaysia Development Berhad scandal|corruption at state fund 1Malaysia Development Berhad]],<ref name=\":1\" /> citing a need to reduce debt incurred by the previous government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/0c8e113c2dae4205a5fc28f567422f00|title=Malaysian PM says China-financed Projects Canceled|date=21 August 2018|agency=Associated Press|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921193619/https://apnews.com/0c8e113c2dae4205a5fc28f567422f00|archive-date=21 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/east-coast-rail-link-and-pipeline-projects-with-china-cancelled-says-malaysian-pm|title=East Coast Rail Link and Pipeline Projects with China to be Deferred|date=21 August 2018|work=Strait Times|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923123844/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/east-coast-rail-link-and-pipeline-projects-with-china-cancelled-says-malaysian-pm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/china/mahathir-fears-new-colonialism-cancels-2-chinese-projects-on-beijing-visit/articleshow/65493634.cms|title=Mahathir fears new colonialism, cancels 2 Chinese projects on Beijing visit \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=23 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904151443/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/china/mahathir-fears-new-colonialism-cancels-2-chinese-projects-on-beijing-visit/articleshow/65493634.cms|archive-date=4 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-20/mahathir-warns-against-new-colonialism-during-visit-to-china|title=Mahathir Warns Against New 'Colonialism' During Visit to China|date=20 August 2018|work=Bloomberg|access-date=23 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823105732/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-20/mahathir-warns-against-new-colonialism-during-visit-to-china|archive-date=23 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Quote|text=It will be deferred until such time we can afford, and maybe we can reduce the cost also if we do it differently.|sign=|source=[[Mahathir Mohamad]]}}\n\nIn addition, Mahathir also threatened to deny foreign buyers a long-stay visa, prompting a clarification by Housing Minister Zuraida Kamaruddin and the Prime Minister's Office.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-05/-100-billion-plan-in-limbo-as-mahathir-welcomes-foreign-buyers|title=Malaysia Leaves $100 Billion Real Estate Project in Limbo|date=5 September 2018|work=Bloomberg|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923125520/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-05/-100-billion-plan-in-limbo-as-mahathir-welcomes-foreign-buyers|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe project undergo negotiations for several months<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/06a71510-b24a-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132|title=Malaysia Cancels China-backed pipeline projects|date=9 September 2018|work=Financial Times|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911002429/https://www.ft.com/content/06a71510-b24a-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132|archive-date=11 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and close to be cancelled off.<ref>{{cite news |title=Malaysia to cancel $20 billion China-backed rail project: minister |date=26 January 2019 |agency=Reuters |work=Business Standard |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/reuters/malaysia-to-cancel-20-billion-china-backed-rail-project-minister-119012600144_1.html |access-date=26 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126111446/https://www.business-standard.com/article/reuters/malaysia-to-cancel-20-billion-china-backed-rail-project-minister-119012600144_1.html |archive-date=26 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> After rounds of negotiation and diplomatic mission, the ECRL project is resumed after Malaysia and China agreed to continue the project with reduced cost of RM 44 billion (US$10.68 billion) from the original of RM 65.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/478726/back-track-ecrl-resume-rm-44-billion|title=Back on track: ECRL to resume at RM 44 billion|date=12 April 2019|work=New Straits Times|access-date=18 April 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418104841/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/478726/back-track-ecrl-resume-rm-44-billion|archive-date=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\n{{Main|China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor}}\nThe [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor]] is a major Belt and Road Initiative project encompassing investments in transport, energy and maritime infrastructure.\n\n====Sri Lanka====\nChina's main investment in [[Sri Lanka]] was the [[Magampura Mahinda Rajapaksa Port]], mostly funded by the Chinese government and built by two Chinese companies. It claims to be the largest port in [[Sri Lanka]] after the Port of [[Colombo]] and the \"biggest port constructed on land to date in the country\". It was initially intended to be owned by the [[Government of Sri Lanka]] and operated by the [[Sri Lanka Ports Authority]], however it incurred heavy operational losses and the Sri Lankan government was unable to service the debt to China. In a [[debt restructuring]] plan on 9 December 2017, 70% of the port was leased and port operations were handed over to China for 99 years,<ref name=\":2\" /> The deal gave the Sri Lankan government $1.4 billion, that they will be using to pay off the debt to China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/42235/hambantota-port-agreement-signed|title=Hambantota port agreement signed|website=www.Adaderana.lk|access-date=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002190206/http://www.adaderana.lk/news/42235/hambantota-port-agreement-signed|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/12/world/asia/sri-lanka-china-port.html|title=Sri Lanka, Struggling With Debt, Hands a Major Port to China|access-date=23 August 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822145840/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/12/world/asia/sri-lanka-china-port.html|archive-date=22 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-sri-lanka-port.html|title=How China Got Sri Lanka to Cough Up a Port|work=New York Times|date=25 June 2018|access-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016135624/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/25/world/asia/china-sri-lanka-port.html|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This led to accusations that China was practicing [[debt-trap diplomacy]].<ref name=\"ps\">{{cite web |url= https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/china-one-belt-one-road-loans-debt-by-brahma-chellaney-2017-01 |title= China's Debt-Trap Diplomacy |last= Chellaney |first= Brahma |date= 23 January 2017 |website= Project Syndicate |language=en |access-date= 15 September 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170129090158/https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/china-one-belt-one-road-loans-debt-by-brahma-chellaney-2017-01 |archive-date= 29 January 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe port's strategic location and subsequent ownership spurred concern over China's growing economic footprint in the Indian Ocean and speculation that it could be used as a naval base. The Sri Lankan government promised that it was intended \"purely for civilian use\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/12/sri-lanka-formally-hands-over-hambantota-port-to-chinese-firms-on-99-year-lease/|title=Sri Lanka Formally Hands Over Hambantota Port to Chinese Firms on 99-Year Lease|work=The Diplomat|date=11 December 2017|access-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016164849/https://thediplomat.com/2017/12/sri-lanka-formally-hands-over-hambantota-port-to-chinese-firms-on-99-year-lease/|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Colombo International Financial City]] built on land reclaimed from the Indian Ocean and funded with $1.4bn in Chinese investment is a special financial zone and another major Chinese investment in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2018/aug/02/sri-lanka-new-dubai-chinese-city-colombo |title=Sri Lanka's 'new Dubai': Will Chinese-built city suck the life out of Colombo? |access-date=26 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115090425/https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2018/aug/02/sri-lanka-new-dubai-chinese-city-colombo |archive-date=15 January 2019 |url-status=live |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 August 2018 |last1=Safi |first1=Michael }}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\nIn [[Thailand]] in 2005, the Chinese pharmaceutical company, [[Holley Group]], and the Thai industrial estate developer, [[Amata Group]], signed an agreement to develop the Thai\u2013Chinese [[Rayong Province|Rayong]] Industrial Zone. Since 2012, Chinese companies have also opened [[Solar power|solar]], rubber, and industrial [[manufacturing plants]] in the zone, and the zone expects the number to increase to 500 by 2021.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-china-investment-idUSKCN0Y72D5| title=From car parts to condos, faltering Thailand lures Chinese money| work=Reuters| date=17 May 2016| access-date=16 October 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016125906/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-china-investment-idUSKCN0Y72D5| archive-date=16 October 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> Chinese media have attributed this to Thailand's zero [[tax incentive]]s on land use and export products as well as favorable labor costs, and claimed that the zone had created more than 3000 local jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.cncnews.cn/news/v_show/49239_Thai-Chinese_Rayong_Industrial_Zone.shtml|title=Thai\u2013Chinese Rayong Industrial Zone|work=CNC|access-date=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016125914/http://en.cncnews.cn/news/v_show/49239_Thai-Chinese_Rayong_Industrial_Zone.shtml|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, China and Thailand began the construction of a high-speed railway that links the cities of [[Bangkok]] and [[Nakhon Ratchasima]], which will be extended to [[Nong Khai]] to connect with Laos, as part of the planned [[Kunming\u2013Singapore railway]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chankaew |first1=Prapan |last2=Lefevre |first2=Amy Sawitta |title=After delays, ground broken for Thailand-China railway project |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-china-railway/after-delays-ground-broken-for-thailand-china-railway-project-idUSKBN1EF1E6 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=Reuters |date=21 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018082634/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-china-railway/after-delays-ground-broken-for-thailand-china-railway-project-idUSKBN1EF1E6 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first high-speed rail rail station in Thailand should be complete in 2021, with lines to enter service in 2024.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Citation |last=Leikens |first=David |date=November 17, 2019 |title=Thailand hopes to have bullet trains running by 2023 |publisher=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/thailand-bullet-trains/index.html |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Turkey ====\n[[President Erdogan]] in his visit to China signed a Memorandum of Understanding with China under the Belt and Road Initiative and asked to increase trade volume, Referring to the fact that the volume of trade between the two countries reached $50 billion in the first phase, and in the second phase $100 billion in other goals. Thanks to the [[Baku-Tbilisi-Kars railway]] being integrated with [[Edirne-Kars high-speed train]], projects with China will be able to transport their goods to Europe much sooner.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://uwidata.com/4983-turkey-and-china-one-road-one-belt-project/ |title = Turkey and China One Road One Belt Project|date = 20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== North and South America ===\nPanama was the first to sign BRI agreements, followed by Bolivia, Antigua and Barbuda, Trinidad and Tobago, and Guyana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://supchina.com/2019/01/14/venezuela-china-explained-2/|title=The Venezuela-China relationship, explained: Belt and Road {{!}} Part 2 of 4|date=14 January 2019|website=SupChina|language=en-US|access-date=24 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624005848/https://supchina.com/2019/01/14/venezuela-china-explained-2/|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Argentina ====\nThe Argentine-China Joint Hydropower Project will build two dams on the [[Santa Cruz River (Argentina)|Santa Cruz River]] in southern [[Argentina]]: [[Condor Cliff Dam|Condor Cliff]] and [[La Barrancosa Dam|La Barrancosa]]. The China Gezhouba Group Corporation (CGGC) will be responsible for the project, which is expected to provide 5,000 direct and 15,000 indirect jobs in the country. It will generate 4,950 MWh of electricity, reducing the dependence on fossil fuels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/77500.htm|title=Argentine president calls Argentina-China hydropower project \"highly important\"-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=16 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116200848/https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/77500.htm|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Jamaica ====\nOn 11 April 2019, Jamaica and China signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] for Jamaica to join the BRI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/85836.htm|title=China, Jamaica signed MoU on Belt and Road cooperation-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=24 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624005852/https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/85836.htm|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Financial and research institutions==\n===Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB)===\n{{Infobox Treaty\n|name                = \n|long_name           = [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]]\n|image               =Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank map.svg\n|image_width         =259x259px\n|caption             ={{legend|lightgreen|Prospective members (regional)}}\n{{legend|green|Members (regional)}}\n{{legend|#88ccf9|Prospective members (non-regional)}}\n{{legend|blue|Members (non-regional)}}\n|date_drafted        = \n|date_signed         =\n|location_signed     =\n|date_sealed         =\n|date_effective      =\n|condition_effective =\n|date_expiration     =\n|signatories         =\n|parties             =\n|depositor           =\n|languages           =\n|wikisource          =\n}}\n{{main|Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank}}\nThe [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]], first proposed in October 2013, is a development bank dedicated to lending for infrastructure projects. As of 2015, China announced that over one trillion yuan (US$160 billion) of infrastructure related projects were in planning or construction.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PskwCwAAQBAJ|title=The Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank: The Construction of Power and the Struggle for the East Asian International Order|last=Wan|first=Ming|date=16 December 2015|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=9781137593887|page=70|language=en|access-date=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203062903/https://books.google.com/books?id=PskwCwAAQBAJ|archive-date=3 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe primary goals of AIIB are to address the expanding infrastructure needs across Asia, enhance regional integration, promote economic development and improve the public access to social services.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.aiib.org/en/about-aiib/index.html|title=About AIIB Overview \u2013 AIIB|website=www.aiib.org|language=en|access-date=1 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930084526/https://www.aiib.org/en/about-aiib/index.html|archive-date=30 September 2017|url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nThe Articles of Agreement of the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB) (the legal framework) were signed in [[Beijing]] on 29 June 2015. The proposed bank has an authorized capital of $100 billion, 75% of which will come from Asia and [[Oceania]]. China will be the single largest stakeholder, holding 26.63% of voting rights. The board of governors is AIIB's highest decision-making body.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aiib.org/en/about-aiib/governance/index.html|title=Governance Overview \u2013 AIIB|website=www.aiib.org|language=en|access-date=1 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930084656/https://www.aiib.org/en/about-aiib/governance/index.html|archive-date=30 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The bank began operation on 16 January 2016, and approved its first four loans in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aiib.org/en/news-events/news/2019/20190116_001.html|title=AIIB Turns 3, Reflects on Startup Growth - News - AIIB|website=www.aiib.org|language=en|access-date=16 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117013334/https://www.aiib.org/en/news-events/news/2019/20190116_001.html|archive-date=17 January 2019|url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\n===Silk Road Fund===\n{{for|the main article|Silk Road Fund}}\n\nIn November 2014, [[Xi Jinping]] announced a US$40 billion development fund, which would be separate from the banks and not part of the [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor|CPEC]] investment. The [[Silk Road Fund]] would invest in businesses rather than lend money to the projects. The [[Karot Hydropower Project]], {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Islamabad]], [[Pakistan]] is the first project.<ref>{{cite web|title = Commentary: Silk Road Fund's 1st investment makes China's words into practice|url = http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/04/21/content_281475093213830.htm|website = english.gov.cn|accessdate = 15 July 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150715185219/http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/04/21/content_281475093213830.htm|archive-date = 15 July 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> The Chinese government has promised to provide Pakistan with at least US$350 million by 2030 to finance this station. The Sanxia Construction Corporation commenced work in January 2016.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n===University Alliance of the Silk Road===\n{{Main|University Alliance of the Silk Road}}\nA university alliance centered at [[Xi'an Jiaotong University]] aims to support the Belt and Road initiative with research and engineering, and to foster understanding and academic exchange.<ref name=\"China Daily\">{{cite news  | last = Ma  | first = Lie  | title = University alliance seeks enhanced education co-op along Silk Road  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2016-04/11/content_24446327.htm  | newspaper = [[China Daily]]  | date = 11 April 2016  | accessdate = 18 September 2016  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160918160548/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2016-04/11/content_24446327.htm  | archive-date = 18 September 2016  | url-status = live  }}</ref><ref name=\"UWN\">{{cite web  | last = Yojana  | first = Sharma  | title = University collaboration takes the Silk Road route  | url = http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20150611130705830  | publisher = University World News  | date = 12 June 2015  | accessdate = 18 September 2016  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160819131122/http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20150611130705830  | archive-date = 19 August 2016  | url-status = live  }}</ref> The network extends beyond the economic zone, and includes a [[law school]] alliance to \"serve the Belt and Road development with legal spirit and legal culture\".<ref name=\"China Daily Law\">{{cite news  | last = Ma  | first = Lie  | title = Chinese and foreign law schools launch New Silk Road alliance  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-12/11/content_22693518.htm  | newspaper = [[China Daily]]  | date = 12 November 2015  | accessdate = 18 September 2016  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160918161819/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-12/11/content_22693518.htm  | archive-date = 18 September 2016  | url-status = live  }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n===Background: Infrastructure-based development===\nChina is a world leader in infrastructure investment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/global-themes/winning-in-emerging-markets/chinese-infrastructure-the-big-picture|title=Chinese infrastructure: The big picture|website=McKinsey & Company|language=en|access-date=18 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419054827/https://www.mckinsey.com/global-themes/winning-in-emerging-markets/chinese-infrastructure-the-big-picture|archive-date=19 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In contrast with the general underinvestment in transportation infrastructure in the industrialized world after 1980 and the pursuit of [[Export-oriented industrialization|export-oriented development]] policies in most [[Asia]]n and [[Eastern Europe]]an countries,<ref name=\"Euromoney\">{{cite news|author= M. Nicolas J. Firzli [[World Pensions & Investments Forum|2= World Pensions Council (WPC)]] Director of Research quoted by Andrew Mortimer|title= Country Risk: Asia Trading Places with the West|url= http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3006113/Euromoney-country-risk-Asia-trading-places-with-the-west.html|work= Euromoney Country Risk|date= 14 May 2012|accessdate= 5 May 2017|location= .|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170603132157/http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3006113/Euromoney-country-risk-Asia-trading-places-with-the-west.html|archive-date= 3 June 2017|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"USAK-JTW\">{{cite news|author=M. Nicolas J. Firzli |title= Forecasting the Future: The BRICs and the China Model|url= https://www.academia.edu/12319362| work= International Strategic Organization (USAK) Journal of Turkish Weekly |date= 8 March 2011|accessdate=9 May 2017  | location=.}}</ref> China has pursued an [[infrastructure-based development]] strategy, which has resulted in engineering and construction expertise and a wide range of modern reference projects from which to draw, including roads, bridges, tunnels, and [[high-speed rail]] projects.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.academia.edu/6494981| work= Revue Analyse Financi\u00e8re| location= Paris| title= Transportation Infrastructure and Country Attractiveness| first= M. Nicolas J.| last= Firzli| date= 2013| accessdate= 26 April 2014| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150904095706/http://www.academia.edu/6494981/Transportation_Infrastructure_and_Country_Attractiveness| archive-date= 4 September 2015| url-status= live}}</ref> Collectively, many of China's projects are called \"[[Megainfrastructure|mega-infrastructure]]\".\n\nMembers of the [[World Pensions & Investments Forum|World Pensions Council]] (WPC), a non-profit policy research organization, have argued the Belt and Road initiative constitutes a natural extension of the [[infrastructure-based development|infrastructure-driven economic development]] framework that has sustained the rapid economic growth of China since the adoption of the [[Chinese economic reform]] under chairman [[Deng Xiaoping]],<ref name=\"Firzli 2015\">{{cite news| url= https://www.academia.edu/19535167| work= Revue Analyse Financi\u00e8re| location= Paris| title= China's AIIB, America's Pivot to Asia & the Geopolitics of Infrastructure Investments| first= M. Nicolas J.| last= Firzli| date= 2015| accessdate= 1 October 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160129073111/http://www.academia.edu/19535167/China_s_AIIB_America_s_Pivot_to_Asia_and_the_Geopolitics_of_Infrastructure_Investments| archive-date= 29 January 2016| url-status= live}}</ref> which could eventually reshape the [[Eurasia]]n economic continuum, and, more generally, the international economic order.<ref name=\"Carter Center\">{{cite news |first1=Daniel |last1=Grober |title=New Kid on the Block: The Asian Infrastructure Bank |url=http://www.uscnpm.org/blog/2017/02/09/new-kid-on-the-block-the-asian-infrastructure-bank/ |accessdate=13 May 2017 |work=The Carter Center US-China Perception Monitor |date=February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002022453/https://www.uscnpm.org/blog/2017/02/09/new-kid-on-the-block-the-asian-infrastructure-bank/ |archive-date=2 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xiao Yu|first=Pu|date=2015|title=The Geo-economic effects of OBOR|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312533416|journal=One Belt, One Road: Visions and Challenges of China's Geoeconomic Strategy}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2014 and 2016, China's total trade volume in the countries along the Belt and Road exceeded $3 trillion, created $1.1 billion revenues and 180,000 jobs for the countries involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2015-01/29/c_127433046.htm|title=China Voice: The \"Belt and Road\" initiative brings new opportunities \u2013 Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=news.xinhuanet.com|language=en-US|access-date=1 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412093432/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2015-01/29/c_127433046.htm|archive-date=12 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, partnering countries worry whether the large debt burden on China to promote the Initiative will make China's pledges declaratory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caixinglobal.com/2017-07-18/101117767.html|title=Opinion: China to Confront Financial, Engineering Challenges in 'Belt and Road'|website=www.caixinglobal.com|language=en|access-date=1 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002021838/http://www.caixinglobal.com/2017-07-18/101117767.html|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accusations of neocolonialism===\nThere has been concern over the project being a form of [[neocolonialism]]. Some Western governments have accused the Belt and Road Initiative of being neocolonial due to what they allege as China practice of [[debt trap diplomacy]] to fund the initiative's infrastructure projects.<ref name=\"dmav\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-02-21-iss-today-lessons-from-sri-lanka-on-chinas-debt-trap-diplomacy/ |title=ISS Today: Lessons from Sri Lanka on China's 'debt-trap diplomacy' |last=Today |first=ISS |date=21 February 2018 |website=Daily Maverick |language=en-US |access-date=15 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915231046/https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2018-02-21-iss-today-lessons-from-sri-lanka-on-chinas-debt-trap-diplomacy/ |archive-date=15 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSwaine (2019) describes such accusations as concerns grossly inflated and oversold, attributing repayment problems in individual cases to reckless and inexperienced practices as opposed to premeditation on the part of Chinese investment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swaine|first1=Michael D.|title=A relationship under extreme duress: U.S.-China relations at a crossroads|url=https://carnegieendowment.org/2019/01/16/relationship-under-extreme-duress-u.s.-china-relations-at-crossroads-pub-78159|work=carnegieendowment.org|publisher=Carnegie Endowment for International Peace| date=16 January 2019|access-date=5 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205063004/https://carnegieendowment.org/2019/01/16/relationship-under-extreme-duress-u.s.-china-relations-at-crossroads-pub-78159|archive-date=5 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Chinese government characterizes claims of neocolonialism or debt-trap diplomacy as manipulations to sow mistrust about China's intentions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feldshuh |first1=Hannah |title=China Debates the Belt and Road |url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/09/china-debates-the-belt-and-road/ |work=The Diplomat |date=8 September 2018 |access-date=23 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124003716/https://thediplomat.com/2018/09/china-debates-the-belt-and-road/ |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> China contends that the initiative has provided markets for commodities, improved prices of resources and thereby reduced inequalities in exchange, improved infrastructure, created employment, stimulated industrialization, and expanded technology transfer, thereby benefiting host countries.<ref name=\"blan-revisit\">{{cite news |last1=Blanchard |first1=Jean-Marc F. |title=Revisiting the Resurrected Debate About Chinese Neocolonialism |url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/02/revisiting-the-resurrected-debate-about-chinese-neocolonialism/ |work=The Diplomat |date=8 February 2018 |access-date=23 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123195340/https://thediplomat.com/2018/02/revisiting-the-resurrected-debate-about-chinese-neocolonialism/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Blanchard (2018) argues that the potential scope of the benefits may not be fully recognized and the negatives exaggerated, noting that critics are concerned with disparaging Chinese investments and suggesting that they should shift their focus to empowering host countries instead.<ref name=blan-revisit/> Poghosyan (2018) states that some Chinese experts claim that such Western perceptions of the Belt and Road Initiative are misconstrued due to Western conceptions of development as seen through their own lens of exploitation of others for resources\u2014as exemplified by western European colonialism\u2014instead of through Chinese conceptions of development.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Poghosyan |first1=Benyamin |title=China \u2013 US Relations: The Need for Talks to Overcome Misperceptions |url=http://georgiatoday.ge/news/13323/China-%E2%80%93-US-Relations%3A-The-Need-for-Talks-to-Overcome-Misperceptions- |website=Georgia Today |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=23 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123044818/http://georgiatoday.ge/news/13323/China-%E2%80%93-US-Relations%3A-The-Need-for-Talks-to-Overcome-Misperceptions- |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Set to differentiate from the coercive nature as was characterized by Western colonialism, as stated by Xing (2017), China's strategic paradigm for the Belt and Road Initiative involves the active participation and cooperation of partner countries.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Xing |first1=Guangcheng |title=Looking for A Road: China Debates Its and the World's Future |date=2017 |publisher=Koninklijke Brill / Social Sciences Academic Press |isbn=978-90-04-33080-1 |pages=152\u2013155 |chapter=Understanding China's One-Belt-One-Road Initiative A New Link Pattern for Deepened Interaction between China and the World}}</ref>\n \nIn 2018, [[Malaysia]]n Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad]] cancelled China-funded projects and warns \"there is a new version of Colonialism happening\",{{r|\":1\"}} which he later clarified as not being about China and its Belt and Road Initiative in an interview with the BBC HARDtalk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jaipragas |first1=Bhavan |title=Is China's belt and road colonialism? Mahathir: not at all |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/2166693/chinas-belt-and-road-colonialism-mahathir-not-all |website=South China Morning Post |date=2 October 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124105802/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/2166693/chinas-belt-and-road-colonialism-mahathir-not-all |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dr M: I didn't accuse the Chinese |url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/dr-m-i-didnt-accuse-chinese |website=The Edge Markets |date=3 October 2018 |access-date=27 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124220015/http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/dr-m-i-didnt-accuse-chinese |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Government officials in India have repeatedly objected to China's Belt and Road Initiative, specifically because they believe the \"[[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor]]\" (CPEC) project ignores New Delhi's essential concerns on sovereignty and territorial integrity.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/cpec-route-through-kashmir-could-create-tension-with-india-un-report/story-05fDgjtdFmATT6K13ZJffN.html |title=CPEC route through Kashmir could create tension with India: UN report &#124; world news |work=Hindustan Times |date=22 April 2016 |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511024457/https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/cpec-route-through-kashmir-could-create-tension-with-india-un-report/story-05fDgjtdFmATT6K13ZJffN.html |archive-date=11 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Ecological Issues===\nThe Swiss group Zo\u00ef has identified six areas that need to be given careful attention as BRI projects continue to expand in order to prevent long-term ecological damage. They are: Mining practices to be effectively monitored, efforts to move energy production away from coal to renewable alternatives, infrastructure projects to consider and plan in ways to reduce contributions to climate change (I.e. promoting sustainable land use, shortening travel times and distances, and greater fuel efficiency), protecting the biodiversity of project areas, infrastructure projects to calculate ecological affects into the plans, and care needs to be taken not disrupt traditional lifestyles, \u201clocal ethnic and indigenous groups.\u201d<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Hughes|first=Geoff (ed.)|url=https://zoinet.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/BRI-Layout-WEB.pdf|title=Greening the Belt and Road Projects in Central Asia: A Visual Synthesis|publisher=Zoi Environment Network|year=2019|isbn=|location=Switzerland|pages=}}</ref> \n\nThe ecological concerns are problematic for many BRI opponents. Many examples are available. \u201cChinese-backed [[hydropower]] projects along the [[Mekong|Mekong River]] \u2013 which spans Cambodia, Lao PDR, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam \u2013 have seen dams cause river flow changes and block fish migration, leading to a loss of livelihood for communities there which live-off the river.\u201d <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://theaseanpost.com/article/chinas-bri-negatively-impacting-environment|title=China's BRI negatively impacting the environment|date=December 24, 2019|work=The Asean Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Deforestation and climate change|Deforestation]] in areas such as the [[Pan-Borneo Highway|Pan Borneo Highway]] \u2013 which spans Malaysia, Indonesia and Brunei \u2013 also causes landslides, floods and other disaster mitigation concerns.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Coal-fired power station]]s, such as [[Emba Hunutlu power station]] in [[Turkey]], are being built; thus increasing [[greenhouse gas emissions]] and [[global warming]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e360.yale.edu/digest/chinas-belt-and-road-initiative-could-drive-warming-to-2-7-degrees|title=China's Belt and Road Initiative Could Drive Warming to 2.7 Degrees|website=Yale E360|language=en-US|access-date=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925175240/https://e360.yale.edu/digest/chinas-belt-and-road-initiative-could-drive-warming-to-2-7-degrees|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Glacier melting as a result of excess greenhouse gas emissions, endangered species preservation, [[desertification]] and [[soil erosion]] as a result of [[overgrazing]] and over farming, mining practices, water use management, air and water pollution as a result of poorly planned infrastructure projects are some of the ongoing concerns as they relate to Central Asian nations. <ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Motivation===\n[[File:Roundtable meeting of leaders at Belt and Road international forum.jpg|thumb|Roundtable meeting of leaders at [[Belt and Road Forum]] in 2017]]\nPractically, developing infrastructural ties with its neighboring countries will reduce physical and regulatory barriers to trade by aligning standards.<ref>CSIS China Power Project, [https://chinapower.csis.org/china-belt-and-road-initiative/ How will the Belt and Road Initiative advance China's interests?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929184104/https://chinapower.csis.org/china-belt-and-road-initiative/ |date=29 September 2017 }}, 27 June 2017</ref> China is also using the Belt and Road Initiative to address excess capacity in its industrial sectors, in the hopes that whole production facilities may eventually be migrated out of China into BRI countries.<ref>Peter Cai, [https://www.lowyinstitute.org/sites/default/files/documents/Understanding%20China%E2%80%99s%20Belt%20and%20Road%20Initiative_WEB_1.pdf Understanding China's Belt and Road Initiative] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602113721/https://www.lowyinstitute.org/sites/default/files/documents/Understanding%20China%E2%80%99s%20Belt%20and%20Road%20Initiative_WEB_1.pdf |date=2 June 2017 }} \"Lowy Institute for International Policy\" 27 June 2017</ref>\n\nA report from [[Fitch Ratings]] suggests that China's plan to build ports, roads, railways, and other forms of infrastructure in under-developed Eurasia and Africa is out of political motivation rather than real demand for infrastructure. The Fitch report also doubts Chinese banks' ability to control risks, as they do not have a good record of allocating resources efficiently at home, which may lead to new asset-quality problems for Chinese banks that most of funding is likely to come from.<ref>Peter Wells, Don Weinland, [http://www.ftchinese.com/story/001071181 Fitch warns on expected returns from One Belt, One Road] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303050530/http://www.ftchinese.com/story/001071181 |date=3 March 2017 }}, ''Financial Times'', 26 January 2017</ref>\n\nThe Belt and Road Initiative is believed by some analysts to be a way to extend Chinese influence at the expense of the US, in order to fight for regional leadership in Asia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/11/asia/china-one-belt-one-road-explainer/index.html|title=Just what is this One Belt, One Road thing anyway?|author=James Griffiths|website=CNN|access-date=8 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908155143/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/11/asia/china-one-belt-one-road-explainer/index.html|archive-date=8 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Jamie Smyth, [https://www.ft.com/content/e30f3122-0eae-11e7-b030-768954394623 Australia rejects China push on Silk Road strategy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408082600/https://www.ft.com/content/e30f3122-0eae-11e7-b030-768954394623 |date=8 April 2017 }}, ''Financial Times'', 22 March 2017</ref> Some geopolitical analysts have couched the Belt and Road Initiative in the context of [[Halford Mackinder]]'s [[The Geographical Pivot of History|heartland theory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/01/china-and-the-world-island/|title=China and the World-Island|last=Sempa|first=Francis P.|date=26 January 2019|website=[[The Diplomat]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126023844/https://thediplomat.com/2019/01/china-and-the-world-island/|archive-date=26 January 2019|url-status=|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/03/12/chinas-global-dreams-are-giving-its-neighbors-nightmares/|title=China's Global Dreams Give Its Neighbors Nightmares|last=Daly|first=Robert|date=12 March 2018|website=[[Foreign Policy]]|language=en|access-date=1 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601215808/https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/03/12/chinas-global-dreams-are-giving-its-neighbors-nightmares/|archive-date=1 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-06-10/china-and-russia-want-to-control-the-world-island|title=China and Russia Want to Control the 'World Island'|last=Stavridis|first=James|date=10 June 2019|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=23 June 2019|language=en|author-link=James G. Stavridis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628185323/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-06-10/china-and-russia-want-to-control-the-world-island|archive-date=28 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Scholars have noted that official PRC media attempts to mask any strategic dimensions of the Belt and Road Initiative as a motivation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rolland|first=Nad\u00e8ge|date=12 August 2019|title=Mapping the footprint of Belt and Road influence operations|url=https://sinopsis.cz/en/rolland-bri-influence-operations/|journal=Sinopsis|access-date=25 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925210415/https://sinopsis.cz/en/rolland-bri-influence-operations/|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> China has already invested billions of dollars in several South Asian countries like Pakistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh, and Afghanistan to improve their basic infrastructure, with implications for China's trade regime as well as its military influence. China has emerged as one of the fastest-growing sources of Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) into India \u2013 it was the 17th largest in 2016, up from the 28th rank in 2014 and 35th in 2011, according to India's official ranking of FDI inflows.\n\nAn analysis by the [[Jamestown Foundation]] suggests that the BRI also serves Xi Jinping's intention to bring about \"top-level design\" of economic development, whereby several infrastructure-focused state-controlled firms are provided with profitable business opportunities in order to maintain high GDP growth.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://jamestown.org/program/one-belt-one-road-enhances-xi-jinpings-control-over-the-economy/|title='One Belt, One Road' Enhances Xi Jinping's Control Over the Economy {{!}} Jamestown|website=jamestown.org|language=en-US|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121005723/https://jamestown.org/program/one-belt-one-road-enhances-xi-jinpings-control-over-the-economy/|archive-date=21 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Through the requirement that provincial-level companies have to apply for loans provided by the Party-state to participate in regional BRI projects, Beijing has also been able to take more effective control over China's regions and reduce \"centrifugal forces\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Others have suggested that the BRI is also an attempt to escape the [[middle income trap]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-future-of-chinese-foreign-economic-policy-will-challenge-u-s-interests-part-1-the-belt-and-road-initiative-and-the-middle-income-trap/|title=The Future of Chinese Foreign Economic Policy Will Challenge U.S. Interests, Part 1: The Belt-and-Road Initiative and the Middle Income Trap|last=Saha|first=Sagatom|date=January 29, 2020|website=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nAnother aspect of Beijing's motivations for BRI is the initiative's internal state-building and stabilisation benefits for its vast inland western regions such as Xinjiang and Yunnan. Academic Hong Yu argues that Beijing's motivations also lie in developing these less developed regions, with increased flows of international trade facilitating closer economic integration with the China's inland core.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Hong|date=November 2016|title=Motivation behind China's 'One Belt, One Road' Initiatives and Establishment of the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank|journal=Journal of Contemporary China|volume=26|issue=105|pages=353\u2013368|doi=10.1080/10670564.2016.1245894}}</ref> Beijing may also be motivated by BRI's potential benefits in pacifying China's restive [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] population. Harry Roberts suggests that the Communist Party is effectively attempting to assimilate and pacify China's Uyghur community by using economic opportunities to increase integration between Han settlers and the native population.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Changing Regional Alliances for China and the West|last=Lane|first=David|last2=Zhu|first2=Guichang|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2017|isbn=978-1498562348|location=London|page=94}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions over the world ==\n\n=== Supporters of the project ===\n\n==== Russia ====\nMoscow has been an early partner of China in the New Silk Roads project. President [[Vladimir Putin|Putin]] and President [[Xi Jinping|Xi]] have met several times in the last decade and have already agreed on developments which will be of mutual benefit. In March 2015, Russia's First Deputy Prime Minister Shuvalov asserted that \"Russia should not view the Silk Road Economic Belt as a threat to its traditional, regional sphere of influence [\u2026] but as an opportunity for the [[Eurasian Economic Union]]\u201d. Russia and China now have altogether 150 common projects for Eurasian Union and China. These projects, some under the \"Polar Silk Road\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/opinion/bri-transforming-world-economic-order/|title=BRI transforming world economic order?|website=asiatimes.com|date=25 April 2019|language=en|access-date=4 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823144059/https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/opinion/bri-transforming-world-economic-order/|archive-date=23 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> plan, include gas transmission system, gas refinery plants, manufacturing of vehicles, heavy industries, and new types of services. Not only that, [[China Development Bank]] loaned Russia the equivalent of more than 9.6 billion U.S. dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d3d674d7a41444e34457a6333566d54/index.html|title=What makes Russia an important player in BRI?|website=news.cgtn.com|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623105451/https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d3d674d7a41444e34457a6333566d54/index.html|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An additional proof both countries are growing into a strong partnership is that in official report titled \"The Belt and Road Initiative: Progress, Contributions, and Prospects\" Russia was mentioned 18 times, the most out of all countries except China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/zchj/qwfb/86739.htm|title=The Belt and Road Initiative Progress, Contributions and Prospects-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623105451/https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/zchj/qwfb/86739.htm|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Asia ====\nOne of China's claimed official priority is to benefit its neighbors before everyone else. During the second Belt and Road Forum for International Cooperation which was held in May 2019, Xi Jinping reaffirmed his will to promote regional trade whether it was with President [[Bounnhang Vorachith|Vorachith]] of Laos<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beltandroadforum.org/english/n100/2019/0506/c22-1431.html|title=Xi Jinping Holds Talks with General Secretary of the Central Committee of the Lao People's Revolutionary Party (LPRP) and President Bounnhang Vorachith of Laos.|access-date=30 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830093341/http://www.beltandroadforum.org/english/n100/2019/0506/c22-1431.html|archive-date=30 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> or Prime Minister Lee of Singapore<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beltandroadforum.org/english/n100/2019/0505/c22-1428.html|title=Xi Jinping Meets with Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong of Singapore.|access-date=30 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830093342/http://www.beltandroadforum.org/english/n100/2019/0505/c22-1428.html|archive-date=30 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and that, for the benefit of all the parties. This goes in line with the joint effort decided in November 2015 to move [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]] (ASEAN)-China relation to a higher level of economic cooperation in areas such as Agriculture, IT, Transport, Communications, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asean.org/?static_post=asean-china-free-trade-area-2|title=ASEAN - China Free Trade Agreements|website=ASEAN {{!}} ONE VISION ONE IDENTITY ONE COMMUNITY|language=en-US|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624024134/https://asean.org/?static_post=asean-china-free-trade-area-2|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Singapore''' is already a rich, fully developed economy with global interests, and does not need massive external financing or technical assistance for domestic infrastructure building. Nevertheless it has repeatedly endorsed the Belt-and-Road Initiative and cooperated in related projects. The motivation is a quest for global relevance, and the strengthening of economic ties with BRI recipients. Furthermore there is a strategic defensive factor: making sure the China is not the single dominant factor in Asian economics.<ref>Irene Chan, \"Reversing China\u2019s Belt-and-Road Initiative\u2014Singapore\u2019s Response to the BRI and Its Quest for Relevance.\" ''East Asia'' 36.3 (2019): 185-204.</ref>\n\nAlthough the '''Philippines''' historically has been closely tied to the United States, China has sought its support for the BRI in terms of the quest for dominance in the South China Sea. The Chinese strategy has largely been successful, as the Philippines has adjusted its policy and in favor of Chinese maritime expansion in the South China Sea. Philippines President [[Rodrigo Roa Duterte]] has reversed his predecessors policy of resisting Chinese expansion. He calculates that this will be the economically more beneficial route, expecting a sort of revival of old maritime silk route, and will support his plans for massive infrastructure expansion.<ref>Renato Cruz De Castro,  \"China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) and the Duterte Administration\u2019s Appeasement Policy: Examining the Connection Between the Two National Strategies.\" ''East Asia'' 36.3 (2019): 205-227.</ref>\n\n==== Arab countries ====\nIn April 2019 and during the second Arab Forum on Reform and Development, China engaged in an array of partnerships called \"Build the Belt and Road, Share Development and Prosperity\" with 18 Arab countries. The amount of trade between the two entities has grown almost ten-fold over the last 10 years. That is because China does not see the Middle East as their 'petrol station' anymore. Many further areas of commerce are being involved nowadays; ports in [[Oman]], factories in [[Algeria]], skyscrapers in [[Egypt]]'s new capital, etc. China is interested in providing financial security to those countries, who after many Arab wars and American interventions, live off the U.S support. On the one hand, Arab countries gain independence and on the other, China opens the door of a colossal market. As the president of [[Lebanon]] [[Michel Aoun]] stated, \"We regard China as a good friend and are willing to further consolidate the relationship with China. We would like to draw the experience from China\u2019s reform and development so as to benefit our people and seek our opportunities for development\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/opinion/bri-transforming-world-economic-order/|title=Asia Times {{!}} BRI transforming world economic order {{!}} Opinion|last=Times|first=Asia|website=Asia Times|date=25 April 2019|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509173856/https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/opinion/bri-transforming-world-economic-order/|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An additional advantage on China's part is that it plays a neutral role on the level of diplomacy. China is not interested in intervening between [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Iran]]'s conflict for instance. Therefore, it succeeds in trading with countries which are enemies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/04/20/chinese-money-is-behind-some-of-the-arab-worlds-biggest-projects|title=Chinese money is behind some of the Arab world's biggest projects|date=20 April 2019|work=The Economist|access-date=23 June 2019|issn=0013-0613|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623105455/https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/04/20/chinese-money-is-behind-some-of-the-arab-worlds-biggest-projects|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Africa ====\nAttending the second [[Belt and Road Forum]], former president of the world bank and current president of the [[United Nations Economic Commission for Africa|UNECA]] [[Vera Songwe]] said: \"This (BRI) is probably one of the biggest growths and development initiatives that we have in the world\". The statement well sums up the general stand of African countries. Just like Arab countries, they see the BRI as a tremendous opportunity for independence from the foreign aid and influence. More than half the continent has already signed partnerships with the Middle Kingdom. [[Lu Kang (diplomat)|Lu Kang]], spokesman for China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs recently declared: \"We will advance bilateral cooperation in areas including industries, infrastructure, trade and investment, improve the living standards of African people, bring more development dividends to African countries, and deliver more benefits to people in China and Africa\". Not only that, he continued saying: \"The two sides have already launched many important cooperation projects and achieved early harvests\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africatimes.com/2019/04/18/china-notes-africas-key-bri-role-ahead-of-forum-in-beijing/|title=China notes Africa's key BRI role ahead of forum in Beijing|date=18 April 2019|website=Africa Times|language=en-US|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623105451/https://africatimes.com/2019/04/18/china-notes-africas-key-bri-role-ahead-of-forum-in-beijing/|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Europe ====\n[[File:Wsp\u00f3lne o\u015bwiadczenie w sprawie ustanowienia wszechstronnego strategicznego partnerstwa.jpg|thumb|Xi Jinping and Polish President [[Andrzej Duda]] signed a declaration on strategic partnership between Poland and China]]\n[[Greece]], [[Croatia]] and 14 other eastern Europe countries are already dealing with China within the frame of the BRI. While most of them still suffer the aftereffect of the 2008 economic crisis, proponents argue that China's approach creates a new range of opportunities. In March 2019, Italy was the first member of the [[Group of Seven|Group of Seven nations]] to join the Chinese Initiative. The new partners signed a 2.5 billion euros \u201c[[Memorandum of understanding|Memorandum of Understanding]]\u201d across an array of sectors such as transport, logistics and port infrastructure to strengthen financial cooperation.<ref name=\"Ellyatt\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/27/italys-joins-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative.html|title=Is Italy playing with fire when it comes to China?|last=Ellyatt|first=Holly|date=27 March 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501161750/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/27/italys-joins-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative.html|archive-date=1 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Italian PM immediately affirmed his trust toward China declaring: \"Cooperation is bigger than competition between China and Europe\". Italian PM [[Giuseppe Conte]]'s decision was followed soon thereafter by neighboring countries Luxembourg and Switzerland. A few weeks later, China won another victory by consolidating billions of dollars' worth of infrastructure deals with the [[16+1 Nations]], which changed its name to the 17+1 group, as it saw Greece join the alliance as well. [[Poland]]'s President [[Andrzej Duda]] stated that \"Polish companies will benefit hugely\" from China's Belt and Road Initiative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polish president says Xi Jinping understands central European dynamic |url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2016xivisitee/2016-06/19/content_25763414.htm |work=Chinadaily.com.cn |date=19 June 2016}}</ref> Duda and Xi signed a declaration on [[strategic partnership]] in which they reiterated that Poland and China viewed each other as long-term strategic partners.<ref>{{cite news |title=Xi welcomes Chinese freight train to 'strategic partner' Poland |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-poland-china-xi/xi-welcomes-chinese-freight-train-to-strategic-partner-poland-idUKKCN0Z6205 |agency=Reuters |date=20 June 2016}}</ref> \n\n=== Opponents to the project ===\n\n==== Australia, Japan, India and the US 'Indo-Pacific Vision' ====\n'''Japan,''' '''India''' and '''Australia''' joined forces to create an alternative to the Belt and Road creating the \u201c[https://dailyknowledgefactory.blogspot.com/2020/01/blue-dot-network-counterpart-to-chinas.html '''Blue Dot Network''']\u201d. In reality, very few details are known about the project although it was initiated in 2016. By and large, the cooperation highlighted two topics: securing the Pacific Ocean and guaranteeing free trade in the region.\n\nBy 2019, the '''United States''' joined the initiative thus renaming the alliance into the \"Free and Open Indo-Pacific strategy\" (FOIP). President [[Donald Trump]] has begun translating the U.S. Free and Open Indo-Pacific strategy (FOIP) into more concrete initiatives across what officials have articulated as three pillars \u2013 security, economics, and governance. This can be seen as a direct counterattack against China which expands its military and whose communist roots are viewed by some as antagonistic to the idea of free trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/04/advancing-democracy-in-the-us-free-and-open-indo-pacific-strategy/|title=Advancing Democracy in the US Free and Open Indo-Pacific Strategy|last=Diplomat|first=Prashanth Parameswaran, The|website=The Diplomat|language=en-US|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425155943/https://thediplomat.com/2019/04/advancing-democracy-in-the-us-free-and-open-indo-pacific-strategy/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[World Pensions & Investments Forum|World Pensions Council]] director M. Nicolas J. Firzli has argued that the United States and its allies will strive to court large [[private sector]] asset owners such as [[pension fund]]s, inviting them to play an increasingly important geo-economic part across the [[Asia Pacific]] area, alongside US and other state actors:\n\n{{quote|Even the self-absorbed, thrifty 'America first' policy makers in the White House eventually realized they couldn\u2019t ignore these fateful geo-economic developments. In November 2018, vice-president [[Mike Pence]] travelled to Asia to promote [[Presidency of Donald Trump|President Trump]]'s 'Indo-Pacific Vision', an ambitious plan backed by tens of billions of dollars in new loans and credit-enhancement mechanisms to encourage \"private investment in regional infrastructure assets\", insisting that \"business, not bureaucrats will facilitate our efforts\". The new great game has just started, and pension investors will be courted assiduously by both Washington and Beijing in the coming years \u2013 not a bad position to be in<!--not a mistake--> in the 'age of geoeconomics'.<ref name=TriumphTone>Nicolas Firzli, \"Institutional Investment in the Age of Geoeconomics\" [https://www.ipe.com/reports/special-reports/thought-leadership/thought-leadership-investment-in-the-age-of-geo-economics/10030347.article/ ''Investment & Pensions Europe (IPE)'' 10 April, 2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627163629/https://www.ipe.com/reports/special-reports/thought-leadership/thought-leadership-investment-in-the-age-of-geo-economics/10030347.article/ |date=27 June 2019 }}</ref>}}\n\nAt the beginning of June 2019, there has been a redefinition of the general definitions of \"free\" and \"open\" into four specific principles \u2013 respect for sovereignty and independence; peaceful resolution of disputes; free, fair, and reciprocal trade; and adherence to international rules and norms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://media.defense.gov/2019/May/31/2002139210/-1/-1/1/DOD_INDO_PACIFIC_STRATEGY_REPORT_JUNE_2019.PDF|title=Ministry of US Defense. Indo-Pacific Report June 2019|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626000337/https://media.defense.gov/2019/May/31/2002139210/-1/-1/1/DOD_INDO_PACIFIC_STRATEGY_REPORT_JUNE_2019.PDF|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Leaders committed that the United States and India should intensify their economic cooperation to \"make their nations stronger and their citizens more prosperous\".\n\n'''Vietnam''' historically has been at odds with China for a thousand years, and generally opposes the South China Sea expansion. It in recent decades has been on close terms with the United States and Japan. However, China is so big and so close, that Vietnam has been indecisive about support or opposition to BR.<ref>Ngo Di Lan, and Truong-Minh Vu, \"The Sino-US-Vietnam Triangle in a Belt and Road Era.\" ''East Asia'' 36.3 (2019): 229-241. [http://www.viet-studies.net/kinhte/SinoVNTriangle_Sept19.pdf  Online]</ref>\n\nThe response of ''' South Korea''' has been to evade Chinese overtures and instead try to develop the \"Eurasia Initiative\" (EAI) as its own vision for an East-West connection. In calling for a revival of the ancient Silk Road, the main goal of President [[Park Geun-hye]] was to encourage a flow of economic, political, and social interaction from Europe though the Korean Peninsula. Her successor, President [[Moon Jae-in]] announced his own foreign policy initiative, the |New Southern Policy\" (NSP), which seeks to strengthen relations with Southeast Asia. Both EAI and NSP were proposed to strengthen the long-term goal of peace with North Korea. These policies are the product of the South Korean vulnerability to great power competition. It is trying to build economic ties with smaller powers so as to increase Seoul's foreign policy leverage as a middle power.<ref>Balbina Y. Hwang, \"Northeast Asian Perspectives on China\u2019s Belt Road Initiative: the View from South Korea.\" ''East Asia'' 36.2 (2019): 129-150.</ref>\n\n==== European Union ====\nRecently, Italy and Greece have been the first major powers to join the Belt and Road Initiative, stressing the urgency for the EU to clarify its positions towards China international policies. Indeed, whereas Italy's Deputy Prime Minister [[Luigi Di Maio]] told that the accord was \"nothing to worry about\", French and German leaders are less optimistic. President [[Emmanuel Macron|Macron]] even said in Brussels that \"the time of European na\u00efvet\u00e9 is ended\". \"For many years\", he added, \"we had an uncoordinated approach and China took advantage of our divisions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/05/are-china-france-relations-in-trouble/|title=Are China-France Relations in Trouble?|first=Eleanor|last=Albert|date=2019-05-03|website=The Diplomat|access-date=22 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of March 2019, German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] and European Commission President [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] joined for talks with Xi in Paris in company of President Macron. There, Macron exhorted China to \"respect the unity of the European Union and the values it carries in the world\". Juncker on his end stressed that European companies should find \"the same degree of openness in the China market as Chinese ones find in Europe.\" In the same vein, Merkel declared that the BRI \"must lead to a certain reciprocity, and we are still wrangling over that bit.\" In January 2019 Macron said: \"the ancient Silk Roads were never just Chinese \u2026 New roads cannot go just one way.\"<ref name=\"Ellyatt\"/>\n\nIn late December 2018 Germany tightened its policies around foreign trade, increasing their ability to restrict certain direct or indirect acquisitions of shares in German companies on based on national security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/china-europe-trade-technology-competition-51115/|title=China and Europe: Trade, technology and competition|first=Manoj|last=Joshi|website=ORF|access-date=15 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115070621/https://www.orfonline.org/research/china-europe-trade-technology-competition-51115/|archive-date=15 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs a consequence to the growing criticism of the Belt and Road Initiative and the lacking transparency, European Commission Chief Jean-Claude Juncker and Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe signed an infrastructure agreement in Brussels on the 27<sup>th</sup>of September 2019. This pact between Europe and Japan is ought to counter China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative and link Europe and Asia to coordinate infrastructure, transport and digital projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.european-views.com/2019/09/japan-and-the-eu-sign-infrastructure-deal-to-rival-chinas-belt-and-road/|title=Japan and the EU sign infrastructure deal to rival China's Belt and Road|last=Eva|first=Joanna|date=2019-09-30|website=European Views|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/09/28/business/japan-eu-vow-infrastructure-cooperation-counter-china/|title=Japan and EU ink infrastructure cooperation pact in counter to China's Belt and Road|date=2019-09-28|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, the EU is one of the biggest development donors in the world and many African economies, which are being observed as a backdoor for EU investments and partnerships, have been neglected in recent decades and therefore, the EU fears being outflanked by China and its major investments in the infrastructure in the African region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8656bd1e-e8af-11e9-85f4-d00e5018f061|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nWith regard to the already declining cohesion within the EU, EU diplomats are fearing a further destabilization of the region due to varying China attitudes and policies among the countries and the increasing geopolitical power of China, especially in the South-Eastern countries that are running into big debt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/report-eu-countries-to-be-straitjacketed-by-chinas-new-silk-road/a-43437084|title=Report: EU countries to be straitjacketed by China's New Silk Road {{!}} DW {{!}} 18.04.2018|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nEuropean economists and ambassadors are also rising serious concerns about the impacts of the New Silk Road on the balance of power in International Trade and fear a shift towards China in favor of its highly subsidized and state-owned companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/today/politics/china-first-eu-ambassadors-band-together-against-silk-road/23581860.html|title=China First: EU ambassadors band together against Silk Road|website=www.handelsblatt.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Moreover, the Chinese rise regarding economic success and digitalization and the major comparative advantages the Chinese companies could establish in this field in recent decades are going to challenge European companies in particular and require reforms within the EU in order to ensure the competitiveness of European companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merics.org/de/blog/europe-has-buckle-survive-challenge-belt-and-road|title=Europe has to buckle up to survive the challenge of the \"Belt and Road\" {{!}} Mercator Institute for China Studies|website=www.merics.org|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> \n\nEven though China stated that its massive infrastructural project is going to benefit every country that is being affected, there is apprehension across European countries that the Initiative is going to undermine European environmental and social standards and counter the EU\u2019s agenda for liberalizing trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cirsd.org/en/horizons/horizons-summer-2019-issue-no-14/european-responses-to-bri-an-overdue-assessment|title=European Responses to BRI - An Overdue Assessment|website=CIRSD|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Think tank ===\n\nA French think tank, focused on the study of the New Silk Roads, was launched in 2018. It is described as pro\u2013Belt and Road Initiative and pro-China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observatoirenrs.com/|title=OFNRS - Observer, analyser et conseiller|website=OFNRS|access-date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630123440/https://observatoirenrs.com/|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=November 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Asian Highway Network]]\n* [[Eurasian Land Bridge]]\n* [[Foreign policy of China]]\n* [[Indo-Pacific]]\n* [[List of the largest trading partners of China]]\n* [[Trans-Asian Railway]]\n* [[International North\u2013South Transport Corridor]]\n* [[Asia-Africa Growth Corridor]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|refs =\n<ref name=comp2>\nCompare: {{cite web |url = http://www.ejinsight.com/20160412-getting-lost-one-belt-one-road/ |title= Getting lost in 'One Belt, One Road' |date= 12 April 2016 |publisher= Hong Kong Economic Journal |language=en-US |access-date= 13 April 2016 |quote = Simply put, China is trying to buy friendship and political influence by investing massive amounts of money on infrastructure in countries along the 'One Belt, One Road'. |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160414014511/http://www.ejinsight.com/20160412-getting-lost-one-belt-one-road/ |archive-date= 14 April 2016 |url-status = live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=comp1>\nCompare:\n{{cite document\n | ssrn= 2997650\n | title= What Is One Belt One Road? A Surplus Recycling Mechanism Approach\n | date= 7 July 2017\n | quote = It has been lauded as a visionary project among key participants such as China and Pakistan, but has received a critical reaction, arguably a poorly thought out one, in nonparticipant countries such as the United States and India (see various discussions in Ferdinand 2016, Kennedy and Parker 2015, Godement and Kratz, 2015, Li 2015, Rolland 2015, Swaine 2015).  \n| last1= Chohan\n | first1= Usman W.\n }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=what>\n{{cite web |url = https://www.theguardian.com/cities/ng-interactive/2018/jul/30/what-china-belt-road-initiative-silk-road-explainer |title=What is China's Belt and Road Initiative?|first1=Lily|last1=Kuo|first2=Niko|last2=Kommenda |website=the Guardian |access-date=5 September 2018 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180905062336/https://www.theguardian.com/cities/ng-interactive/2018/jul/30/what-china-belt-road-initiative-silk-road-explainer |archive-date=5 September 2018 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"centralGovernment\">{{cite web\n  |title = China unveils action plan on Belt and Road Initiative\n  |agency = [[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua]]\n  |url = http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/03/28/content_281475079055789.htm\n  |website = Gov.cn\n  |date = 28 March 2015\n  |access-date = 16 April 2018\n  |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180417024034/http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/03/28/content_281475079055789.htm\n  |archive-date = 17 April 2018\n  |url-status = live\n  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=vision>{{cite news |title=Vision and Actions on Jointly Building Belt and Road |url=http://english.cri.cn/12394/2015/03/29/2941s872030_1.htm |agency=Xinhua |date=29 March 2015 |access-date=28 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085441/http://english.cri.cn/12394/2015/03/29/2941s872030_1.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=li