{"title_page": "Balkanska Street", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{GNG|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Balkanska Street\n| marker_image            =\n| native_name             = \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430\n| native_name_lang        = sr\n| alternate_name          = \n| image                   = File: Balkanska 2.jpg\n| image_size              = 250px\n| image_alt               = \n| image_map               = \n| caption                 = Upper section of Balkanska Street\n| map_type                = \n| map_size                = \n| map_caption             = \n| map_alt                 = \n| other_name              = \n| former_names            = \n| part_of                 = \n| namesake                = [[Balkans]]\n| type                    = \n| owner                   = \n| maint                   = \n| length                  = \n| length_m                = 700\n| length_ft               = \n| length_km               = \n| length_mi               = \n| length_ref              = \n| length_notes            = \n| width                   = \n| area                    = \n| addresses               = \n| location                = [[Stari Grad, Belgrade|Stari Grad]] and [[Savski Venac]]\n| arrondissement          = \n| quarter                 = \n| postal_code             = \n| metro                   = \n| coordinates             = \n| direction_a             = \n| terminus_a              = \n| direction_b             = \n| terminus_b              = \n| junction                = \n| north                   = \n| east                    = \n| south                   = \n| west                    = \n| main_contractor         = \n| cost                    = \n| references              = \n| commissioning_date      = \n| construction_start_date = \n| completion_date         = \n| inauguration_date       = 1872\n| demolition_date         = \n| designer                = \n| known_for               = \n| status                  = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Balkanska Street''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430}} / ''Balkanska ulica'', {{trans|Balkan Street}}) is a street in downtown [[Belgrade]], a capital of [[Serbia]]. It is one of the most recognizable streets in the city and one of the oldest still bearing its original name since the first official naming of the city streets in 1872. It is located in the municipalities of [[Stari Grad, Belgrade|Stari Grad]] and [[Savski Venac]]. It has been described as \"one of the most popular downtown streets, where the past and present dwell simultaneously\",<ref name=rekon>{{cite news | author = Milan Jankovi\u0107 | title = \u041e\u0434 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0442 - \u0420\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435 | trans-title = One to five - Reconstruction of Balkanska | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 9 July 2018 }}</ref> and one of Belgrade's liveliest streets.<ref name=rok>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = I tre\u0107i rok za Balkansku ulicu | trans-title = Third deadline for the Balkanska Street | newspaper = Politika | page = 12 | language = Serbian | date = 1 December 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/417048/I-treci-rok-za-Balkansku-ulicu}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\n[[File: Balkanska ulica Beograd.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Lower section]]\n\nBalkanska originates at the [[Terazije]] Square, sole center of Belgrade. Its entire course, some 700 meters, is in the southern direction. It receives a short ''Pajsijeva'' street from the right and then crosses the ''Kraljice Natalije'' street, where it leaves the municipality of Stari Grad and enters Savski Venac. It then receives the ''Lomina'' street from the right and passes through the intersection where it crosses the streets of ''Gavrila Principa'', ''Admirala Geprata'' and ''Milovana Milovanovi\u0107a''. It ends at the meeting with the [[Nemanjina Street]], though its natural extension is the ''Hajduk Veljkov Venac'' and further, ''Sarajevska'' street.<ref>{{cite book|title=Beograd - plan grada|date=2006|publisher=M@gic M@p|isbn=86-83501-53-1}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe street was constructed in 1872, when it got its name it still bears today. Originally, it was routed as a connection between the ''Abad\u017eijska'' (modern ''Kraljice Natalije'') and ''Savamalska'' (modern ''Gavrila Principa'' streets. This entire section of the city was projected by the Viennese architect Franz Janke. First proper building in the street was built in 1876, at the corner with the ''Abad\u017eijska''. In 1885, a tailor (''abad\u017eija'') \u0110or\u0111e Arsenijevi\u0107 opened his tailor store in that building and placed a plastered relief of a scissors on the building's front fa\u00e7ade. As it was prolongued on both sides, it became the direct, and shortest, connection between downtown and [[Savamala]], on the bank of the [[Sava|Sava river]]. In the 19th century, Balkanska was famous for its artisan shops: tailors, waxers, ''[[Opanak|opan\u010dari]]'', quilters. In the 20th century it became known for the food, as a location of some of the best pastries in Belgrade, especially known for its ice-creams and [[halva]]. At the top of the street one of the first fast-food facilities in Belgrade was open, \"Leskov\u010danin\", which used to sell ''[[Pljeskavica|Leskova\u010dka pljeskavica]]''.<ref name=\"b92\">{{cite web|url= http://www.b92.net/putovanja/destinacije/evropa.php?&nav_id=468720|author=|title= Balkanska - zanatlijska ulica|date=29 December 2010|publisher=[[B92]]|language=Serbian}}</ref> In general, Balkanska was a place where you could buy almost any type of goods. Today, only few of the old craftsman's shops survived, like pastry shops and bakeries, but as of 2015, the tanner shop, hat maker or purse tailor can still be found in the street.<ref name=\"Politika\">{{Citation | last = | first = | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107| title = Balkanska - lepotica izboranog lica| newspaper = [[Politika]] | pages =  | language = Serbian | date = 8 February 2015| url = }}</ref>\n\nSome of the oldest, still operational shops are bakery \"An\u0111elko\" (est. 1920), purse tailor \"Zlatko\" (est. 1946) and hatter \"Kapa Rade\" (est. c.1949).<ref name=rok/> In the 1960s, the street was known for the illegal street traders who were selling \"the best English fabrics\".<ref>{{cite news | author = Milo\u0161 Lazi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u041f\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0446\u0435 - \u0421\u0435\u043b\u043e \u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0442\u0435\u0437\u0433\u0430\u043c\u0430 | trans-title = Farmers markets - Village among market stalls | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1156 | page = 22 | language = Serbian | date = 24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn order the preserve the craftsmanship for which the street was known, city government announced in July 2017 the project of adapting the ''Balkanska'' into the \"street of the old crafts\", not only as a tourist attraction but as a way of keeping the \"spirit of Belgrade\".<ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author =Branka Vasiljevi\u0107  | title = Obnovljena Skadarlijska \u010desma | newspaper = Politika | pages = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 8 July 2017 | url = }}</ref> In April 2018 it was announced that the small shops in the street will be reconstructed, the fa\u00e7ades will be renovated and those which are empty will be offered to the artisans from other parts of the city.<ref>{{ cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Balkanska - ulica starih zanata | trans-title = Balkanska - street of old crafts | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 4 May 2018 }}</ref> The reconstruction began on 10 July 2018 and is expected to last until 15 October.<ref name=rekon/> The [[asphalt concrete]] will be removed from the street completely and replaced with the stone slabs on the sidewalks while the street itself will be paved with cobblestone, like it was before. After the reconstruction is complete, the street will be declared a \"special tourist zone\".<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Majstori od danas u Svetogorskoj i Balkanskoj | trans-title = Workers in Svetogorska and Balkanska from today | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 10 July 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/407034/Majstori-u-Svetogorskoj-i-Balkanskoj }}</ref>\n\nHowever, the works dragged on, an in October it was evident that they will be finished only in 2019. The digging of the street actually damaged the business of the remaining craft shops. some of them losing up to 80% of revenue and considering, at least temporary closing of the business.<ref>{{cite news | author = Milan Jankovi\u0107 | title = Od jedan do pet - Ulica balkanska | trans-title = 1 to 5 - Balkan Street | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 22 October 2018}}</ref> The deadline was then moved to 1 December and then to 7 December, and that only for the lower half of the street, while the frequent complete absence of workers was noticeable. City promised that it will not charge the rent to those shops which are renting the government and city owned facilities and that entrepreneurs will be free of paying taxes during the extended reconstruction, however several artisan shops were closed.<ref name=rok/>\n\n== Geography ==\n\nMajor physical feature, by which Balkanska is best known, is its continual steepness, from the beginning to the end. It connects central city plateau, located on the top of Terazije ridge, with the Sava bank and Savamala neighborhood. As Savamala is location of the [[Belgrade Main railway station]], [[Belgrade Bus Station|Belgrade Main Bus Station]] and the Sava port, for over a century Balkanska was the first part of Belgrade travelers would see as it is the shortest way to reach downtown. In the latest decades that changed, though, as none of the public transportation lines go through the Balkanska due to its narrowness.<ref name=\"b92\"/><ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\nEntire underground is rich in groundwater which flow under the entire course of the street. When and underground garage was built on Zeleni Venac, an entire underground lake was discovered.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nMost of the buildings in Balkanska originate from the 1920s and 1930s, with beautiful fa\u00e7ades which are mostly in bad shape due to the lack of maintenance.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\nUpper section of the street is paved, while the lower one is still covered with cobblestone.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\nBeginning and the upper part of the street is the location of the [[Hotel Moskva, Belgrade|Hotel Moskva]], [[Terazijska Terasa]], Terazije fountain and Hotel Prag. There is also an underground passage which connects it to the city's main street, ''Kralja Milana''. Also, the upped course of Balkanska is the easternmost border of the neighborhoods of [[Zeleni Venac]] and Savamala. One of the most popular places in the street was a cinema \"20th October\", now defunct. Ending section is a location of the Hotel Beograd and [[Park Gavrilo Princip]].\n\nIt is known as one of the \"most popular streets in Belgrade\".\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Savski Venac]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{GNG|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name                    = Balkanska Street\n| marker_image            =\n| native_name             = \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430\n| native_name_lang        = sr\n| alternate_name          = \n| image                   = File: Balkanska 2.jpg\n| image_size              = 250px\n| image_alt               = \n| image_map               = \n| caption                 = Upper section of Balkanska Street\n| map_type                = \n| map_size                = \n| map_caption             = \n| map_alt                 = \n| other_name              = \n| former_names            = \n| part_of                 = \n| namesake                = [[Balkans]]\n| type                    = \n| owner                   = \n| maint                   = \n| length                  = \n| length_m                = 700\n| length_ft               = \n| length_km               = \n| length_mi               = \n| length_ref              = \n| length_notes            = \n| width                   = \n| area                    = \n| addresses               = \n| location                = [[Stari Grad, Belgrade|Stari Grad]] and [[Savski Venac]]\n| arrondissement          = \n| quarter                 = \n| postal_code             = \n| metro                   = \n| coordinates             = \n| direction_a             = \n| terminus_a              = \n| direction_b             = \n| terminus_b              = \n| junction                = \n| north                   = \n| east                    = \n| south                   = \n| west                    = \n| main_contractor         = \n| cost                    = \n| references              = \n| commissioning_date      = \n| construction_start_date = \n| completion_date         = \n| inauguration_date       = 1872\n| demolition_date         = \n| designer                = \n| known_for               = \n| status                  = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Balkanska Street''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430}} / ''Balkanska ulica'', {{trans|Balkan Street}}) is a street in downtown [[Belgrade]], a capital of [[Serbia]]. It is one of the most recognizable streets in the city and one of the oldest still bearing its original name since the first official naming of the city streets in 1872. It is located in the municipalities of [[Stari Grad, Belgrade|Stari Grad]] and [[Savski Venac]]. It has been described as \"one of the most popular downtown streets, where the past and present dwell simultaneously\",<ref name=rekon>{{cite news | author = Milan Jankovi\u0107 | title = \u041e\u0434 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0442 - \u0420\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435 | trans-title = One to five - Reconstruction of Balkanska | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 9 July 2018 }}</ref> and one of Belgrade's liveliest streets.<ref name=rok>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = I tre\u0107i rok za Balkansku ulicu | trans-title = Third deadline for the Balkanska Street | newspaper = Politika | page = 12 | language = Serbian | date = 1 December 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/417048/I-treci-rok-za-Balkansku-ulicu}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\n[[File: Balkanska ulica Beograd.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Lower section]]\n\nBalkanska originates at the [[Terazije]] Square, sole center of Belgrade. Its entire course, some 700 meters, is in the southern direction. It receives a short ''Pajsijeva'' street from the right and then crosses the ''Kraljice Natalije'' street, where it leaves the municipality of Stari Grad and enters Savski Venac. It then receives the ''Lomina'' street from the right and passes through the intersection where it crosses the streets of ''Gavrila Principa'', ''Admirala Geprata'' and ''Milovana Milovanovi\u0107a''. It ends at the meeting with the [[Nemanjina Street]], though its natural extension is the ''Hajduk Veljkov Venac'' and further, ''Sarajevska'' street.<ref>{{cite book|title=Beograd - plan grada|date=2006|publisher=M@gic M@p|isbn=86-83501-53-1}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe street was constructed in 1872, when it got its name it still bears today. Originally, it was routed as a connection between the ''Abad\u017eijska'' (modern ''Kraljice Natalije'') and ''Savamalska'' (modern ''Gavrila Principa'' streets. This entire section of the city was projected by the Viennese architect Franz Janke. First proper building in the street was built in 1876, at the corner with the ''Abad\u017eijska''. In 1885, a tailor (''abad\u017eija'') \u0110or\u0111e Arsenijevi\u0107 opened his tailor store in that building and placed a plastered relief of a scissors on the building's front fa\u00e7ade. As it was prolongued on both sides, it became the direct, and shortest, connection between downtown and [[Savamala]], on the bank of the [[Sava|Sava river]]. In the 19th century, Balkanska was famous for its artisan shops: tailors, waxers, ''[[Opanak|opan\u010dari]]'', quilters. In the 20th century it became known for the food, as a location of some of the best pastries in Belgrade, especially known for its ice-creams and [[halva]]. At the top of the street one of the first fast-food facilities in Belgrade was open, \"Leskov\u010danin\", which used to sell ''[[Pljeskavica|Leskova\u010dka pljeskavica]]''.<ref name=\"b92\">{{cite web|url= http://www.b92.net/putovanja/destinacije/evropa.php?&nav_id=468720|author=|title= Balkanska - zanatlijska ulica|date=29 December 2010|publisher=[[B92]]|language=Serbian}}</ref> In general, Balkanska was a place where you could buy almost any type of goods. Today, only few of the old craftsman's shops survived, like pastry shops and bakeries, but as of 2015, the tanner shop, hat maker or purse tailor can still be found in the street.<ref name=\"Politika\">{{Citation | last = | first = | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107| title = Balkanska - lepotica izboranog lica| newspaper = [[Politika]] | pages =  | language = Serbian | date = 8 February 2015| url = }}</ref>\n\nSome of the oldest, still operational shops are bakery \"An\u0111elko\" (est. 1920), purse tailor \"Zlatko\" (est. 1946) and hatter \"Kapa Rade\" (est. c.1949).<ref name=rok/> In the 1960s, the street was known for the illegal street traders who were selling \"the best English fabrics\".<ref>{{cite news | author = Milo\u0161 Lazi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u041f\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0446\u0435 - \u0421\u0435\u043b\u043e \u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0442\u0435\u0437\u0433\u0430\u043c\u0430 | trans-title = Farmers markets - Village among market stalls | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1156 | page = 22 | language = Serbian | date = 24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn order the preserve the craftsmanship for which the street was known, city government announced in July 2017 the project of adapting the ''Balkanska'' into the \"street of the old crafts\", not only as a tourist attraction but as a way of keeping the \"spirit of Belgrade\".<ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author =Branka Vasiljevi\u0107  | title = Obnovljena Skadarlijska \u010desma | newspaper = Politika | pages = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 8 July 2017 | url = }}</ref> In April 2018 it was announced that the small shops in the street will be reconstructed, the fa\u00e7ades will be renovated and those which are empty will be offered to the artisans from other parts of the city.<ref>{{ cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Balkanska - ulica starih zanata | trans-title = Balkanska - street of old crafts | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 4 May 2018 }}</ref> The reconstruction began on 10 July 2018 and is expected to last until 15 October.<ref name=rekon/> The [[asphalt concrete]] will be removed from the street completely and replaced with the stone slabs on the sidewalks while the street itself will be paved with cobblestone, like it was before. After the reconstruction is complete, the street will be declared a \"special tourist zone\".<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Majstori od danas u Svetogorskoj i Balkanskoj | trans-title = Workers in Svetogorska and Balkanska from today | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 10 July 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/407034/Majstori-u-Svetogorskoj-i-Balkanskoj }}</ref>\n\nHowever, the works dragged on, an in October it was evident that they will be finished only in 2019. The digging of the street actually damaged the business of the remaining craft shops. some of them losing up to 80% of revenue and considering, at least temporary closing of the business.<ref>{{cite news | author = Milan Jankovi\u0107 | title = Od jedan do pet - Ulica balkanska | trans-title = 1 to 5 - Balkan Street | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 22 October 2018}}</ref> The deadline was then moved to 1 December and then to 7 December, and that only for the lower half of the street, while the frequent complete absence of workers was noticeable. City promised that it will not charge the rent to those shops which are renting the government and city owned facilities and that entrepreneurs will be free of paying taxes during the extended reconstruction, however several artisan shops were closed.<ref name=rok/>\n\n== Geography ==\n\nMajor physical feature, by which Balkanska is best known, is it's continual steepness, from the beginning to the end. It connects central city plateau, located on the top of Terazije ridge, with the Sava bank and Savamala neighborhood. As Savamala is location of the [[Belgrade Main railway station]], [[Belgrade Bus Station|Belgrade Main Bus Station]] and the Sava port, for over a century Balkanska was the first part of Belgrade travelers would see as it is the shortest way to reach downtown. In the latest decades that changed, though, as none of the public transportation lines go through the Balkanska due to its narrowness.<ref name=\"b92\"/><ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\nEntire underground is rich in groundwater which flow under the entire course of the street. When and underground garage was built on Zeleni Venac, an entire underground lake was discovered.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nMost of the buildings in Balkanska originate from the 1920s and 1930s, with beautiful fa\u00e7ades which are mostly in bad shape due to the lack of maintenance.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\nUpper section of the street is paved, while the lower one is still covered with cobblestone.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\nBeginning and the upper part of the street is the location of the [[Hotel Moskva, Belgrade|Hotel Moskva]], [[Terazijska Terasa]], Terazije fountain and Hotel Prag. There is also an underground passage which connects it to the city's main street, ''Kralja Milana''. Also, the upped course of Balkanska is the easternmost border of the neighborhoods of [[Zeleni Venac]] and Savamala. One of the most popular places in the street was a cinema \"20th October\", now defunct. Ending section is a location of the Hotel Beograd and [[Park Gavrilo Princip]].\n\nIt is known as one of the \"most popular streets in Belgrade\".\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Savski Venac]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography:spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balkanska_Street"}
{"title_page": "List of original (pre-war) Martin D-45s", "text_new": "This is a list of the 91 original (pre-war) [[Martin D-45]]s made by [[C.F. Martin & Co.]] between the years 1933 and 1942, generally recognized to the most desired, and highly valued, [[acoustic guitars]] ever made; in \"American Guitars - An Illustrated History\", author Tom Wheeler describes them as \"among American guitar's irreplaceable treasures\".<ref>Wheeler, Tom. American Guitars - An Illustrated History. Harper & Row, 1982 {{ISBN|0062731548}}</ref> It is not known exactly how many still survive, however as information is available in print form or via web information, sale inventories, and so on it can be collated here.\n\n== Serial numbers and years, with notes as available ==\nThe listing of serial numbers presented below is from Mike Longworth's book \"Martin Guitars - A History\",<ref>Longworth, Mike. 1975. {{Google books|UlvkAAAAMAAJ|Martin Guitars - A History}}. Omnibus Press, Revised edition 2008. Hal Leonard; {{ISBN|0634037854}}</ref> while associated information is from other sources as available, one particularly valuable source being the  [http://d-45masterlist.blogspot.com/ ''Martin D-45 Master List''] maintained by Robert (Bob) Hamilton and Bruce Herrmann.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\">{{cite web|url=http://d-45masterlist.blogspot.com/|title=Martin D-45 Master List at blogspot.com}}</ref> Instruments marked \"[E]\" are those known to exist according to either information contained herein or a separate version of the ''Martin D-45 Master List''.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\">{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/martind45masterlist/|title=Martin D-45 Master List at sites.google.com}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n!s/n!!Year!![E]!!Description\n|-\n| 53177 || 1933 || [E] || Special order for [[Gene Autry]], \"Gene Autry\" on fingerboard, 12 fret model with slotted head and \"torch\" inlay on headstock, currently in the Autry National Center in Los Angeles; photographs and other information available here.<ref name=\"autrycollections\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autrycollections.org/mwebcgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=M510017;type=101 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217050616/http://www.autrycollections.org/mwebcgi/mweb.exe?request=record%3Bid%3DM510017%3Btype%3D101 |archive-date=2015-02-17 |url-status=dead |title=guitar |accessdate=2015-09-06 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 56394 || 1934 || [E] || Made for Jackie \"Kid\" Moore, 12 fret model with solid headstock featuring \"torch\" inlay. Presently in Hank Risan's Museum of Modern Instruments (MOMI) collection.<ref name=\"themomi.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/Dreadnoughts/1934JackieKidMooreMartinD-45.html|title=TheMoMI.org -- The Museum of Musical Instruments -- The Hank Risan Collection|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Featured in \"Acoustic Guitar\" \"Great Acoustics\" section, December 1999.<ref name=\"themomi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/articles/singingcowboys/images/2.jpg|title=Image: 2.jpg, (254 \u00d7 280 px)|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 63715 || 1936 || [E] || First 14 fret model (14 frets clear of the body), special wide body (16 1/4 Inches). On loan to, and on display at, the Martin Museum in Nazareth from collector Sten Juhlas according to.<ref name=\"yuku\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/D45-how-many-are-known-to-remain-today?page=3|title=D-45 - how many are known to remain today? in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref><ref name=\"premierguitar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/articles/20677-pre-war-perfection-the-martin-d-45?page=3|title=Pre-War Perfection: The Martin D-45 &#124; Premier Guitar|publisher=premierguitar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Shown in this video<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O4-I_Alw8fQ Martin D-45S 1936 Authentic Acoustic Guitar]</ref> from the Martin Museum.\n|-\n| 64890 || 1936 || [E] || D-45S Special wide body (16 1/4 Inches). Illustrated on p.&nbsp;207 of Arlen Roth, \"Complete Acoustic Guitar\", 1985 (photo provided by Gruhn Guitars, Nashville),<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Arlen Roth Complete Acoustic Guitar|author=Roth, A.|publisher=Music Sales Group|isbn=9780857127525|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1OhZc9UClmIC&pg=PA207|page=207|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> also on p.&nbsp;263 of the hardcover version of George Gruhn/Walter Carter book \"Acoustic Guitars and Other Fretted Instruments\" where it is credited to \"Steve Shaw\", therefore potentially included in the collection of the late Steven Kern Shaw (refer \"Miscellaneous\" section).\n|-\n| 65265 || 1937 || &nbsp; || 2 pick guards according to the ''D-45 master list''; current existence not known\n|-\n| 67460 || 1937 || [E] || Third and last 12 fret model, all remainder are 14 frets; the only 12 fret instrument with solid (non slotted) head and vertical \"C F Martin\" inlay as per 14-fret models. Made for Harold A. Wagler, initials \"HAW\" in fingerboard. Illustrated on p.&nbsp;248 of<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Evans, Tom & Mary Anne, \"Guitars from the Renaissance to Rock\", Paddington Press, 1977</ref> and on page 263 of the hardcover version of George Gruhn/Walter Carter book \"Acoustic Guitars and Other Fretted Instruments\". Additional background information and photos of this guitar available here.<ref name=\"yuku2\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/55397/Re-Martin-guitar-registry|title=Martin guitar registry? in The Vintage Corner Archives Volume III Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 70592 || 1938 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> ||\n|-\n| 70593 || 1938 || [E] ||  Illustrated in the \"Martin Guitar Book\", also \"The Vintage Guitar Vol. 3\"\n|-\n| 70594 || 1938 || \n|-\n| 71039 || 1938 || [E] || Previously owned by [[Red Smiley]], now in the collection of Mac Yasuda,<ref>https://www.facebook.com/groups/615182848602758/</ref> illustrations (from Japanese magazine) here.<ref name=\"chiefnoda.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chiefnoda.com/pict/pwd45/index.html|title=Pre-war D-45's|publisher=chiefnoda.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> This instrument has ornamental rhinestones inserted into the head, snowflake inlays have been replaced by more \"modern\" hexagons (engraved \"RED\" and \"D-45\" at the 12th and 19th frets, respectively), also the original D-45 back has been replaced by a later D-28 back at some point. Now in the collection of Mac Yasuda. Illustrated in his book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\".\n|-\n| 71040 || 1938 || [E] || Owned at some point by [[David Bromberg]], many repaired cracks in top, illustrated here.<ref name=\"facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MartinD45/photos/a.404929629526018.101467.403591896326458/888052011213775/?type=1|title=Martin D-45 - Timeline Photos &#124; Facebook|publisher=facebook.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> At some time in Japan, illustrations (from Japanese magazine) here.<ref name=\"chiefnoda.com\"/> For sale at Gruhn in 2009 for $110,000 (inventory no. AA7972), additional discussion here.<ref name=\"yuku3\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/81081/1938-D45-at-Gruhn|title=1938 D-45 at Gruhn in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>  Illustrated in his book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\n|-\n| 71041 || 1938 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page.,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/D45-how-many-are-known-to-remain-today?page=4|title=Martin D-45 Master List|work=martind45howmanyp4}}</ref> having been repaired in his workshop. It is cited as having forward-X bracing, snowflake inlay and being in excellent condition.\n|-\n| 71663 || 1938 || [E] || Special order with unique (?, for a D-45) sunburst top, tortoiseshell headstock veneer, F-9 (archtop) style hexagon fingerboard inlays (the latter later adopted as standard on D-45s from 1939 onwards) and additional white stripes on edges of fingerboard (also as per F-9 archtop). The \"Teeter Guitar\", owned at one time by noted repairman Don Teeter and illustrated on the cover his 1980 book \"Acoustic Guitar: Adjustment, Care, Maintenance and Repair Volume II\",<ref name=\"amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Acoustic-Guitar-Adjustment-Maintenance-Repair/dp/0806116072/|title=Acoustic Guitar: Adjustment, Care, Maintenance and Repair Volume II (2): Don E. Teeter: 9780806116075: Amazon.com: Books|publisher=amazon.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> also featured on the cover of \"Frets\" magazine, May 1988 and in the \"Encore\" section of \"Guitar Player\" magazine, February 1992<ref name=\"themomi2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/articles/Dreadnoughts/images/Feb_1992_GP.jpg|title=Image: Feb_1992_GP.jpg, (254 \u00d7 280 px)|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> and as a foldout on page 49 of the 1st edition of Walter Carter's Martin book. Sold by Lark Street Music in 1987 for $18,000 according to this interview with Buzzy Levine;<ref name=\"blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://kenlelen.blogspot.com.au/2010_07_01_archive.html|title=Vintage Music Concerts: July 2010|publisher=kenlelen.blogspot.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> presently in Hank Risan's Museum of Modern Instruments (MOMI) collection.<ref name=\"themomi.org\"/> Some additional discussion of this instrument here<ref name=\"yuku4\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/1595/Teeter-D45|title=Teeter D-45 in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 71664 || 1938 || [E] || Apparently was in Japan, illustrated on pp.&nbsp;23\u201324 of the (Japanese) \"Martin Vintage Guitar Guide\",<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Martin-Vintage-Guitar-Guide-VA/dp/4779619068|title=Martin Vintage Guitar Guide: 2013. editor: To\u00cc&quot;kyo\u00cc&quot; : San&#39;eishobo\u00cc&quot;: 9784779619069: Amazon.com: Books|publisher=amazon.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> pages also reproduced here<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> Now in US.\n|-\n| 71665 || 1938 || [E] || \"Possibly the last D-45 with snowflake inlays in fretboard\", illustrated here.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/>  illustrated in \"The Vintage Guitar Vol. 3\"\n|-\n| 72160 || 1939 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> formerly owned by Jim Rickard.<ref name=\"jim_rickard\">{{cite web|url=http://ovationfanclub.com/megabbs/forums/thread-view.asp?tid=15628&start=1&posts=6|title=Jim Rickard's former Martin D-45|publisher=ovationfanclub.com|accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref> This instrument was used by [[Tony Rice]] on one track \"I Don\u2019t Want Your Mandolins Mister\" of his 1994 duet CD \"[[Tone Poems (Dave Grisman and Tony Rice album)|Tone Poems]]\" with [[David Grisman]], and is illustrated on the cover of \"Acoustic Guitar\" magazine, January 1996, reproduced here.<ref name=\"steve_acoustic_guitar_magazine\">{{cite web|url=http://musicmansteve.com/Maghome/AcousticGuitar.htm|title=ACOUSTIC GUITAR Magazine Backissues|publisher=musicmansteve.com|accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref> Most recently in the collection of the late Steven Kern Shaw, now on display in the collection of instruments bequeathed by him to Belmont University<ref name=\"belmont_news\" />, as described and illustrated in this forum post.<ref name=\"umgf_t202370\">{{cite web|url=https://umgf.com/1939-d-45-s-n-72160-has-been-located-t202370.html|title=1939 D-45 , S/N 72160 , has been located|publisher=umgf.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72161 || 1939\n|-\n| 72162 || 1939\n|-\n| 72460 || 1939 || [E] || D-45S. The 'S' was for a 'special neck' which was narrower than 1 11/16\". Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> having been for sale at Gruhn around 1990, said to be on consignment for Wilma Lee Cooper, was in somewhat poor condition. Now restored by TJ Thompson after 8 years. Formerly in the collection Mac Yasuda; llustrated his book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\". Listed for sale at Carter Vintage Guitars, Nashville, as at March 2020, asking price $145,000.<ref name=\"cartervintage-72460\">{{cite web|url=https://cartervintage.com/products/martin-d-45-1939|title=Martin D-45S 1939 Product Code: GF3989}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72740 || 1939 || [E] || Known to exist, repaired by Martin during the period 1966-2001 according to this blog post.<ref name=\"martind45-repairs-1966-2001\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/180739/The-91-Pre-War-D45s|title=The 91 Pre War D-45s}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72741 || 1939 || [E] || \"Mother Maybelle\", owned by [[Stephen Stills]];<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> some additional information here<ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=Clapton's Guitar: Watching Wayne Henderson Build the Perfect Instrument|author=St. John, A.|date=2005|publisher=Free Press|isbn=9780743281980|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Eql1iLRGyAC&pg=PA33|page=33|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72742 || 1939\n|-\n| 73126 || 1939\n|-\n| 73127 || 1939 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> ||\n|-\n| 73128 || 1939 || [E] || Owned at one time by [[Johnny Smith]].<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> Seen at Gruhn Guitars, January 2013;<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> advertised for sale by Steve Swan Guitars, February 2015,<ref name=\"steveswanguitars\">{{cite web|url=http://www.steveswanguitars.com/items/vintage-martin-dreadnought/1939-martin-d-45/|title=1939 Martin D-45 - Steve Swan Guitars|publisher=steveswanguitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> for $150,000, since removed from sale; additional picture here<ref name=\"theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/master/1/?page=3|title=D-45 - how many are known to remain today? in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 73129 || 1939 || [E] || Mentioned and illustrated in this thread,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp5\"/> for sale via Gruhn Guitars in 2012, asking price $185,000 (inventory no. AA8729). Purchased by Jim Irsay, CEO/Owner of the Indianapolis Colts.<ref name=\"indystar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/music/2013/12/04/life-by-the-strings/3872185/|title=It's life by the strings for Jim Irsay's guitar man|publisher=indystar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 73130 || 1939 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> having been repaired in his workshop, cited as being sold by Gruhn: most likely as illustrated here<ref name=\"gruhn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gruhn.com/features/45s/AA7540.html |title=Gruhn Guitars Martin D-45 |publisher=web.archive.org |accessdate=2015-09-06 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615143624/http://www.gruhn.com/features/45s/AA7540.html |archivedate=June 15, 2007 }}</ref> (archived copy of web page from 2007)\n|-\n| 73131 || 1939 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> || Now in Japan.\n|-\n| 74011 || 1939 || [E] || D-45S Special order for country singer Ken MacKenzie, with singer's name inlaid in the fingerboard, see photos here.<ref name=\"mackenziewsd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mackenziewsd.com/MaineCountry/photo.html|title=MacKenzie Photo Album|publisher=mackenziewsd.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Appears (with 11 other prewar D-45s) in a photograph of guitars from the Mac Yasuda collection in \"The Vintage Guitar volume 3\", copy and relevant information here<ref name=\"yuku6\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/master/1/?page=4|title=D-45 - how many are known to remain today? in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Illustrated Mac Yasuda's book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\".\n|-\n| 74161 || 1940 || [E] || Previously owned by the well known Martin historian Mike Longworth and was on display in the Martin museum from 1974 to 1995 according to this article<ref name=\"mcall\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1995-04-23/business/3039220_1_d-45-guitar-christie-s-new-York|title=Christie's To Auction Prized Martin Guitar Collection L.v. Man's Love To Be Instrument Of His Retirement - tribunedigital-mcall|publisher=articles.mcall.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> prior to being consigned to auction at Christie's in April 1995 (the guitar failed to sell at that time). A 1981 photograph of this guitar in the Martin museum is available here.<ref name=\"yuku12\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/82326/Mike-Longworth-and-the-Martin-Guitar-Museum|title=Mike Longworth and the Martin Guitar Museum in The D28 Lounge Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 74162 || 1940\n|-\n| 74163 || 1940 || [E] || Single owner till 1987; sold by Gruhn Guitars in 2019, see here;<ref name=\"umgf-74163\">{{cite web|url=https://umgf.com/1940-d-45-s-n-74163-recently-sold-by-gruhn-guitars-t199429.html|title=1940 D-45 , S/N 74163 , Recently Sold by Gruhn Guitars)}}</ref> original finish, sale price $335,000. Description on the Gruhn site here (inventory number: AA10792).<ref name=\"gruhn-aa10792\">{{cite web|url=https://guitars.com/inventory/aa10792-1940-martin-d-45|title=Martin D-45 1940 Product Code: AA10792}}</ref>\n|-\n| 74164 || 1940\n|-\n| 74165 || 1940 || [E] || Presently owned by [[Marty Stuart]], previously by [[Johnny Cash]] and [[Hank Williams, Jr.]], see here;<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp5\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/master/1/?page=5|title=D-45 - how many are known to remain today? (page 5)}}</ref> also additional information below, in \"Miscellaneous\" section.\n|-\n| 74166 || 1940 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> ||\n|-\n| 75100 || 1940 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> || Once owned by Bernie Leaden of Eagles. Now in the collection of Mac Yasuda.\n|-\n| 75101 || 1940 || [E] || Sold by Gruhn Guitars in 2012 (inventory number AA6071), illustrated at,<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> see also,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guitars.com/archived-inventory/D45/AA6071.html|title=Featured Inventory Archives 1999-2012|work=Gruhn Guitars}}</ref> the same instrument illustrated with a sold price $165,000 on this web page about the 2012 Dallas International Guitar Festival.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/billrobinson/backstage-pass-the-dallas_b_1556031.html|title=BACKSTAGE PASS: The Dallas International Guitar Festival ... My Search for the World's Most Valuable Guitar&nbsp;&#124;&nbsp;Bill_Robinson|publisher=huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 75102 || 1940 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> ||\n|-\n| 75103 || 1940\n|-\n| 75104 || 1940 || [E] || Known to exist, repaired by Martin during the period 1966-2001 according to this blog post;<ref name=\"martind45-repairs-1966-2001\" /> currently in Japan in the collection of the well known popular singer [[Fukuyama Masaharu]].<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp5\"/>\n|-\n| 75105 || 1940 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> seen at Gruhn Guitars. Refinished.\n|-\n| 75289 || 1940 || [E] || D-45L (Left hand). In the same family since the 1940s, in the United States.<ref name=\"leftyfrets\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leftyfrets.net/showthread.php?8392-1940-d45L&p=101193|title=1940 d45L - LeftyFrets.net|publisher=leftyfrets.net|accessdate=2016-05-03}}</ref> Original finish.  \n|-\n| 75593 || 1940\n|-\n| 75594 || 1940 || [E] || In the collection of Mac Yasuda, illustrated on the front cover of the \"Martin Guitar Book\", see reference below\n|-\n| 75595 || 1940 || [E] || Nicknamed \"Old Red\", formerly owned by Grant Boatright, see here.<ref name=\"facebook2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MartinD45/photos/a.404929629526018.101467.403591896326458/889141167771526/?type=1|title=Martin D-45 - Timeline Photos &#124; Facebook|publisher=facebook.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> This guitar is presently in the collection of [[Jonathan Kellerman]],<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> and is included (among other guitars from his collection) in an article in \"Vintage Guitar\", October 2005.<ref name=\"vintageguitar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vintageguitar.com/17888/collection-of-jonathan-kellerman/|title=Collection of Jonathan Kellerman &#124;|publisher=vintageguitar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 75596 || 1940 || [E] || Illustrated on a Japanese website here,<ref name=\"tcgakki\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcgakki.com/fair/71c.html#st|title=THE\u4e2d\u53e4\u697d\u5668\u5c4b/\u697d\u5668\u8cb7\u53d6\u308a\u3068\u8ca9\u58f2\uff5c\u81f3\u9ad8\u306e\u9038\u54c1\u3001\u30d7\u30ea\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30fb\u30de\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30f3\u304c\u5947\u8de1\u306e\u5927\u96c6\u7d50!!|publisher=tcgakki.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> also on pp.&nbsp;27\u201328 of the (Japanese) \"Martin Vintage Guitar Guide\",<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/> pages also reproduced here.<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> Currently in the collection of Nakakita Hideki, where it has been nicknamed [[Asano Yoshinaga]] after a 16th Century Japanese samurai warrior.<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp5\"/>\n|-\n| 75597 || 1940\n|-\n| 75598 || 1940 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref n