es/SB113769058643050979|title=That&#39;s One Big, Beautiful Guitar - WSJ|publisher=wsj.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> more pictures here.<ref name=\"facebook3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MartinD45/posts/890992114253098|title=Martin D-45 - Photos taken during my second trip to the... &#124; Facebook|publisher=facebook.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Has oversize pickguard.\n|-\n| 82567 || 1942\n|-\n| 82568 || 1942 || [E] || Offered on eBay in July 2008, sold for $350,000 according to this forum page.<ref name=\"yuku9\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/63565/Prewar-D45-on-eBay|title=Prewar D-45 on eBay in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Illustrated here.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/>\n|-\n| 82569 || 1942 || [E] || Previously belonged to [[Wilma Lee Cooper]], sold by Gruhn (twice: last offered for $195,000 in August 2016, inventory no. AA9807<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160818222519/http://guitars.com/inventory/aa9807-1942-martin-d-45</ref>) and presently in the possession of country/folk/Americana performer [[Gillian Welch]]; see \"Miscellaneous\" section for more information in this and Wilma Lee Cooper's other original D-45.\n|-\n| 82570 || 1942 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> seen at North Carolina guitar show circa 1991.\n|-\n| 82571 || 1942 || [E] || Originally owned and played by Judge Lloyd Rea of Judge Lloyd Rea and the Oregon Trailblazers, see photo here.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://umgf.com/d-45s-on-stage-in-the-40-s-and-50-s-t157387-s20.html?sid=1b069bee792ab0f606a992b52afe8938|title=D-45s on stage in the 40s and 50s - page 2|publisher=umgf.com|accessdate=2018-08-12}}</ref> Listed on eBay in February 2006, sold for $255,100 according to this forum page.<ref name=\"larriveeforum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.larriveeforum.com/smf/index.php?action=printpage;topic=10274.0|title=Print Page - $192,100 but reserve not met.|publisher=larriveeforum.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Recent illustration here.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/>\n|-\n| 82572 || 1942 || [E] || Last \"original series\" D-45 made, subject of an article in \"Great Acoustics\" section of \"Acoustic Guitar\" magazine, May 2000, facsimile available here.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> (According to this blog post<ref name=\"jim_rickard\"/> the actual guitar illustrated is incorrect, and is in fact 1939 instrument #72160 previously owned by Jim Rickard). Most recently in the collection of the late Steven Kern Shaw, now on display in the collection of instruments bequeathed by him to Belmont University<ref name=\"belmont_news\" />, as described and illustrated in this forum post.<ref name=\"umgf_t202346\">{{cite web|url=https://umgf.com/the-last-pre-war-d-45-s-n-82572-made-in-1942-has-b-t202346.html|title=The last Pre-War D-45 , S/N 82572 , made in 1942 has been located|publisher=umgf.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Miscellaneous==\nGeorge Gruhn, the well known Nashville instrument dealer talks in this 2010 interview with \"Guitar International\" magazine<ref name=\"guitarinternational\">{{cite web|url=http://guitarinternational.com/2010/07/02/george-gruhn-talks-banjos-vintage-guitars-and-snakes/|title=George Gruhn Interview : Guitar Interviews|publisher=guitarinternational.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> about his one time considerable collection of vintage style 45 Martin instruments including 6 pre-war D-45s. This collection was sold in 1976 to finance the purchase of his house and the building in which his business was located. The \"best sounding\" (1942) D-45 was sold to Kentucky musician and repairman Harry Sparks for $7,500<ref name=\"sparks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nkytribune.com/2015/06/where-the-pick-hits-the-string-the-music-and-luthier-wizardry-of-harry-sparks/|title=Where the pick hits the string: The music and luthier wizardry of the incredible Harry Sparks|publisher=Northern Kentucky Tribune|accessdate=2016-02-24}}</ref> and can be seen in this video interview of [[Vince Gill]],<ref name=\"gillinterview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/2365673146/|title=Kentucky Collectibles - Vince Gill's Vintage Guitars|publisher=PBS|accessdate=2016-02-24}}</ref> who also owned the instrument for a while and has it on loan as at 2016 (serial number not known).\n\nThe well known  U.S.-based Japanese collector [[Mac Yasuda]] has an extensive collection of American vintage guitars including 14 original D-45s according to this report<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/nov/13/entertainment/ca-53404|title=Heavy Metal - latimes|publisher=articles.latimes.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> among others, some of which are detailed in the section above. In 2001 he published \"The Vintage Guitar Vol. 3\" which includes one photo of 12 D-45s as reproduced here,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> as well as individual photos of 4 instruments. In 2010 he published another illustrated book in Japan, the \"Martin Guitar Book\" as detailed here,<ref name=\"amazon2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/Martin-Guitar-Book-%E3%82%B7%E3%83%B3%E3%82%B3%E3%83%BC%E3%83%BB%E3%83%9F%E3%83%A5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B8%E3%83%83%E3%82%AFMOOK-YASUDA/dp/4401748123|title=Amazon.co.jp\uff1a Martin Guitar Book(\u30b7\u30f3\u30b3\u30fc\u30fb\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30afMOOK): MAC YASUDA: \u672c|publisher=amazon.co.jp|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> which shows two D-45s (one pre-war s/n 75594, one recent) on the front cover. Among his collection is a 1940 (or 1941) D-45 previously owned by [[Bernie Leadon]],<ref name=\"vintagemartin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vintagemartin.com/styles15_17_18.html|title=Style 15, 17, and 18|publisher=vintagemartin.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref><ref name=\"ampage\">{{cite web|url=http://forum.ampage.org/forum.php?cmd=vt&tid=36805|title=Guitar setup tips - AMPAGE Forum|publisher=forum.ampage.org|accessdate=2015-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305035418/http://forum.ampage.org/forum.php?cmd=vt&tid=36805|archive-date=2016-03-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> another is s/n 74011 originally custom built for Ken MacKenzie (see relevant entry in main numeric section above); another is reportedly an instrument previously owned and played by [[Charlie Monroe]] which was purchased new in 1942.<ref name=\"groups.google.com\">https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/bit.listserv.bgrass-l/FQWIV1Bl9as</ref> Mr Yasuda is shown holding one of his D-45s, with a portion of his collection behind, in this photograph.<ref name=\"yasudaphoto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.com.au/detail/news-photo/guitarsngold-2-bg-7nov97mac-yasuda-playing-his-martin-d45-news-photo/569166771#guitarsngold2bg7nov97mac-yasuda-playing-his-martin-d45-infront-of-him-picture-id569166771|publisher=Getty Images|title=LS.Guitars'n'Gold.2.BG.7nov97--Mac Yasuda playing his Martin D45|accessdate=2017-03-21}}</ref>\n\nThe late Steven Kern Shaw, son of well known clarinetist [[Artie Shaw]] and grandson of Broadway composer [[Jerome Kern]], has donated his substantial collection of iconic 20th century American-made instruments - including historic Gibson mandolins and Martin guitars - to [[Belmont University]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] as of November 2016, where they went on display in a museum opened in Spring 2017.<ref name=\"belmont_news\">{{cite web|url=http://news.belmont.edu/the-gallery-of-iconic-guitars-the-gig-opens-on-campus-of-belmont-university/|title=The Gallery of Iconic Guitars, The GIG, Opens on Campus of Belmont University|publisher=belmont.edu|accessdate=2018-05-07}}</ref> This collection includes four pre-war Martin D-45s according to this press release,<ref name=\"belmont_news1\">{{cite web|url=http://news.belmont.edu/belmont-announces-new-interactive-vintage-instrument-museum-to-open-spring-2017/|title=Historically significant guitars to fill interactive museum at Belmont|publisher=belmont.edu|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> which also shows George Gruhn holding one of the pre-war D-45s (a 1939 instrument); the collection includes #82572, the last pre-war D-45 made, and also #72160 as well.<ref name=\"umgf_t202346\" /><ref name=\"umgf_t202370\" />\n\n[[Marty Stuart]] currently owns and performs with a 1940 D-45 (#74165) which he obtained from [[Johnny Cash]]. The instrument has a pearl patch in the front (engraved \"CASH\") where some spruce was once damaged (example photos here<ref name=\"maninblack\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maninblack.net/Guitars/Martin%20D45.html|title=Johnny Cash Guitars|publisher=maninblack.net|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> and here<ref name=\"thegearpage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thegearpage.net/board/showthread.php?t=1300155|title=What is your Dream Guitar? &#124; The Gear Page|publisher=thegearpage.net|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>). Tut Taylor states here<ref name=\"yuku10\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/reply/1559820/Marty-Stuarts-D45|title=Marty Stuart's D-45... in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> that he originally acquired the guitar and sold it to Hank Williams, Jr, who later traded it to Johnny Cash; the same site includes some pictures of this guitar as originally published in \"Best of Guitar Player: Vintage Gallery\", July 1994. (The assertion repeated in Vintage Gallery that the guitar once belonged to Hank Williams, Sr., appears to be incorrect cf. the Tut Taylor recollection cited). A recent article on Stuart and his collection in \"Guitar Aficionado\" magazine here<ref name=\"guitaraficionado\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guitaraficionado.com/how-marty-stuart-is-keeping-country-musics-rich-tradition-alive.html|title=How Marty Stuart Is Keeping Country Music\u2019s Rich Tradition Alive &laquo; Guitar Aficionado|publisher=guitaraficionado.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> discusses this instrument in some depth. A second D-45 previously belonging to both Cash and Stuart is mentioned in this forum post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/166375/Johnny-Cash-a-beatup-D45-not-D28?page=2|title=Johnny Cash a beat-up D-45 (not D-28) (page 2)|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2016-03-30}}</ref>\n\nAt some point, Gruhn Guitars sold 2 Martin D-45s previously belonging to [[Wilma Lee Cooper]], dated 1938 (this one with snowflake inlays and an oversize pickguard, previously owned by Lee Moore, Gruhn inventory number AA6291, serial number not known) and 1942 (s/n 82569, Gruhn inventory number AA6290; the latter is mis-labelled a D-43 on the Gruhn site). The guitars are illustrated here,<ref name=\"guitars\">{{cite web|url=http://guitars.com/archived-inventory/wilmalee/wilmalee.html|title=Featured Inventory Archives 1999-2012 &#124; Gruhn Guitars|publisher=guitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> including this picture<ref name=\"guitars2\">{{cite web|url=http://guitars.com/sites/default/features-archive/wilmalee/AA6291photo.jpg|title=Image: AA6291photo.jpg, (504 \u00d7 620 px)|publisher=guitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> of Wilma Lee with the 1938 guitar; at that time the 1942 D-45 had a sale price of $100,000. More recently, the 1942 instrument was again sold by Gruhn in 2016 (inventory no. AA9087, asking price $195,000) and is now owned by performer and songwriter [[Gillian Welch]];<ref name=\"yuku11\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/152612/Gillian-Welchs-D45|title=Gillian Welch's D-45 in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> this picture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uofmusic.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/GillianWelch-D-45BampW01_zpsb0f979d6.jpg|title=Gillian Welch \u2013 Wayside Back In Time|publisher=uofmusic.com|accessdate=2018-02-19}}</ref> shows Gillian on stage with this guitar.\n\nActor and some time guitarist [[Steven Seagal]] possesses a pre-war D-45 with snowflake inlays (presumably 1937\u20131938) according to a 2006 interview with \"Vintage Guitar\" magazine reproduced here.<ref name=\"steven-seagal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.steven-seagal.net/xen/index.php?threads/guitar-collection-of-steven-seagal.6624/|title=Guitar Collection Of Steven Seagal &#124; Unofficial Steven Seagal|publisher=steven-seagal.net|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nThis video<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=twrmy-31Yh4</ref> of the Songbirds Guitar Museum in Chattanooga includes footage of 2 pre-war Martin D-45s in that collection: one is no. 78629 (1941) as mentioned in the main list, the date and serial number of the other is not known at this time.\n\nA 1939 D-45 (serial number not stated) is illustrated and discussed by George Gruhn in the July 2004 issue of \"Vintage Guitar\" magazine.<ref name=\"vintageguitar2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vintageguitar.com/3268/1939-martin-d-45/|title=1939 Martin D-45 &#124;|publisher=vintageguitar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nA 1940 D-45 (serial number not stated) is presently in Hank Risan's Museum of Modern Instruments (MOMI) collection.<ref name=\"themomi3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/Dreadnoughts/marttrio.html|title=TheMoMI.org -- The Museum of Musical Instruments -- The Hank Risan Collection|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> This collection also houses a 1941 D-45 formerly owned by [[Bob Wills]], serial number not stated.<ref name=\"themomi4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/singcowboys/JackieKidMoore1934MartinD-45_1941MartinD-45.html|title=TheMoMI.org -- The Museum of Musical Instruments -- The Hank Risan Collection|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nA 1940 D-45 (serial number not stated) was being offered for sale by Gruhn Guitars in 2008/9 (inventory no. AA7977), asking price unknown.<ref name=\"yuku3\"/> Another 1940 D-45 (serial number not stated), refinished, is on sale at Gruhn for $195,000 as at June 2015 (inventory no. AA9506).<ref name=\"guitars3\">{{cite web|url=http://guitars.com/inventory/aa9506-1940-martin-d-45|title=AA9506 Martin D-45 1940|publisher=guitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615144241/http://guitars.com/inventory/aa9506-1940-martin-d-45|archivedate=2015-06-15}}</ref>\n\nA 1940 D-45 (serial number not stated) in superb condition, photographed in the UK is illustrated in this Getty Images entry;<ref name=\"gettyimages\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.com.au/detail/news-photo/studio-still-life-of-a-1940-martin-d-45-acoustic-guitar-news-photo/103151510|title=Studio still life of a 1940 Martin D-45 acoustic guitar, photographed... News Photo &#124; Getty Images|publisher=gettyimages.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> the same image is used as an example of a 1940 D-45 on p.&nbsp;33 of \"The Ultimate Guitar Sourcebook\" by Tony Bacon.<ref name=\"google5\">{{cite book|title=The Ultimate Guitar Sourcebook|author=Bacon, T.|date=2012|publisher=MBI Publishing Company|isbn=9781610588423|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f1H0AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA33#v=onepage|page=33|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nU.S. Country artist [[Doyle Dykes]] owns a 1940 D-45 (serial number not stated, pictured in the May 2020 issue of Vintage Guitar magazine.<ref name=\"vintageguitar_May_2020\">{{cite web|url=https://cloud.3dissue.com/196659/197012/230687/VGMMAY20206b579av9/index.html?page=38|title=Doyle's D-45: A vintage treasure returns home|publisher=vintageguitar.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>. According to the article, at one point in the 1950s this instrument had to be returned to the Martin factory for a replacement top, and was fitted with a \"plain\", D-28 style top lacking the distinctive D-45 abalone trim. The guitar was originally owned by Dykes' uncle Doyle \"Smitty\" Smith, a professional guitarist in Washington, D.C., and came into Dykes' possession on his uncle's death; in 1988 Dykes gifted the instrument to country artist [[Roy Clark]], and on the latter's death in 2018, his widow returned the instrument to Dykes. A photograph of this instrument in the hands of its original owner, before its top replacement, is included in the magazine article, and shows it to have originally been fitted with an unusual, large and asymmetrical double pickguard.<ref name=\"vintageguitar_May_2020\" />\n\nA 1941 D-45 (serial number not stated, no other information given) is illustrated here.<ref name=\"offsetguitars\">{{cite web|url=http://www.offsetguitars.com/forums/viewtopic.php?f=31&t=21077|title=OffsetGuitars.com &bull; View topic - Zhivago's Vintage Hotties - 1941 Martin D-45|publisher=offsetguitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nA 1941 D-45 (serial number not stated), refinished with \"multiple professionally repaired top cracks\" and other issues was being offered for sale by Gruhn Guitars in 2007, inventory no. AA7628, asking price $85,000.<ref name=\"yuku13\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/56803/The-91-PreWar-D45s|title=The 91 Pre-War D-45's in The Vintage Corner Archives Vol VI Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nA 1942 D-45, in superb condition (serial number not stated), was featured in \"Vintage Guitar\" magazine, May 2009, copy available here.<ref name=\"vintageguitar3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vintageguitar.com/3887/1942-martin-d-45/|title=1942 Martin D-45 &#124;|publisher=vintageguitar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nA 1942 D-45 (serial number not stated, peghead repair by Dan Erlewine) was being offered for sale by Gruhn Guitars in 2007, asking price $175,000, inventory no. AA7596<ref name=\"yuku13\"/> subsequently sold, archived details shown on Gruhn web site here.<ref name=\"guitars4\">{{cite web|url=http://guitars.com/archived-inventory/1942D45/AA7596.html|title=Featured Inventory Archives 1999-2012 &#124; Gruhn Guitars|publisher=guitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\nThis Facebook page<ref name=\"facebook4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MartinD45|title=Martin D-45 &#124; Facebook|publisher=facebook.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> includes photos of various D-45s, both original and reissues.\n\nAn article entitled \"Martin D-45: A Chronicle of the Jewelled Dreadnought\" appeared in the Japanese magazine \"Acoustic Guitar Magazine\", volume 4,  Spring 2000 (Rittor Music, 2000)<ref name=\"AGM4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hmv.co.jp/en/artist_%E6%A5%BD%E8%AD%9C_000000000508717/item_%E3%82%A2%E3%82%B3%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B9%E3%83%86%E3%82%A3%E3%83%83%E3%82%AF%E3%82%AE%E3%82%BF%E3%83%BC-%E3%83%AA%E3%83%83%E3%83%88%E3%83%BC%E3%83%9F%E3%83%A5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B8%E3%83%83%E3%82%AF%E3%83%A0%E3%83%83%E3%82%AF_777918|title=Acoustic Guitar Magazine 4 (Rittor Music Mook)|accessdate=2017-02-12}}</ref>\n\nSome links to vintage film clips featuring Wilma Lee Cooper and Red Smiley playing their pre-war D-45s are given here.<ref name=\"yuku14\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/110964|title=videos of antique D-45's in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Other 1930s-1940s country stars who have been pictured with their D-45s include [[Gene Autry]] (owner of the first D-45 guitar), Jackie \"Kid\" Moore,<ref name=\"moore1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/Dreadnoughts/Jackie.html|title=Jackie \"Kid\" Moore and his 1934 Martin D-45|publisher=www.themomi.org|accessdate=2016-02-03}}</ref> [[Jimmy Martin]].<ref>https://www.martinguitar.com/media/4557/vol_6.pdf</ref> [[Charlie Monroe]],<ref name=\"groups.google.com\"/> [[Skeeter Bonn]], Toby Stroud,<ref name=\"premierguitar2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/articles/20677-pre-war-perfection-the-martin-d-45|title=Pre-War Perfection: The Martin D-45 &#124; Premier Guitar|publisher=premierguitar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Ken MacKenzie,<ref name=\"mackenzie1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mackenziewsd.com/MaineCountry/photo.html|title=MacKenzie Photo Gallery|publisher=www.mackenziewsd.com|accessdate=2016-02-03}}</ref> Smiley Maxedon (see information above for #81578) and [[Cowboy Slim Rinehart|Nolan \"Cowboy Slim\" Rinehart]].\n\n==Value==\nWhen last available new from the Martin Guitar Company, the 1942 D-45 retailed at $250 (letter from Martin Guitar Company to Mr. Harold Wagler dated October 1963, reproduced here<ref name=\"yuku15\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/161273/Martin-guitar-registry-HAW-D45-HAW-D45?page=4|title=Martin guitar registry? - H.A.W. D-45 - HAW D-45 in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>), equivalent to approximately $3,630 in 2014 dollars as a straight conversion,<ref name=\"measuringworth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.measuringworth.com/|title=Measuring Worth - Relative Worth Calculators and Data Sets|publisher=measuringworth.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> however bearing in mind average incomes of the time, could be construed as between $6,700 and $11,100 in today's terms (same reference, calculated as labor value/income value). In accordance with its gradual acceptance as possibly the finest production steel-string acoustic guitar ever made, the value of an all original, pre-war Martin D45 has gone up considerably over the past 70+ years. In a Vintage Guitar Price Survey published by \"Frets\" magazine in May 1988, a 1939 D-45 in mint condition was estimated at average dealer price $15,000 (range $6,000-$22,000) and a 1942 D-45 (similar) at $13,000 (range $6,000-$21,000). By 2002 the Vintage Guitar Price Guide<ref>Alan Greenwood & Gil Hembree, 2002. The Official Vintage Guitar Magazine Price Guide 2002. Vintage Guitar Books, 2001</ref> listed prices of up to $200,000 for 1936\u20131937 D-45s and up to $150,000 for 1940\u20131942 models. By 2011 a valuation of $375,000 was being cited for a newly discovered 1942 example,<ref name=\"Tony Conley\"/> with values suggested elsewhere<ref name=\"yuku16\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/167538/Gday-Mate-Mr-1941-D45-Serial-Number-78634?page=1|title=G'day Mate! Mr. 1941 D-45 , Serial Number 78634 in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> in the range $175,000-$350,000 according to condition and rarity. According to a post in the Unofficial Martin Guitar Forum, a  1938 snowflake D-45 with forward-X bracing in \"excellent original condition\" recently changed hands for $400,000 in a private sale.<ref name=\"yuku17\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/171265/MOST-VALUABLE-VINTAGE-MARTIN-GUITAR-EVER?page=2|title=MOST VALUABLE VINTAGE MARTIN GUITAR EVER in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Acoustic guitars|Martin]]\n[[Category:Lists of musical instruments|Martin D-45s]]\n", "text_old": "This is a list of the 91 original (pre-war) [[Martin D-45]]s made by [[C.F. Martin & Co.]] between the years 1933 and 1942, generally recognized to the most desired, and highly valued, [[acoustic guitars]] ever made; in \"American Guitars - An Illustrated History\", author Tom Wheeler describes them as \"among American guitar's irreplaceable treasures\".<ref>Wheeler, Tom. American Guitars - An Illustrated History. Harper & Row, 1982 {{ISBN|0062731548}}</ref> It is not known exactly how many still survive, however as information is available in print form or via web information, sale inventories, and so on it can be collated here.\n\n== Serial numbers and years, with notes as available ==\nThe listing of serial numbers presented below is from Mike Longworth's book \"Martin Guitars - A History\",<ref>Longworth, Mike. 1975. {{Google books|UlvkAAAAMAAJ|Martin Guitars - A History}}. Omnibus Press, Revised edition 2008. Hal Leonard; {{ISBN|0634037854}}</ref> while associated information is from other sources as available, one particularly valuable source being the  [http://d-45masterlist.blogspot.com/ ''Martin D-45 Master List''] maintained by Robert (Bob) Hamilton and Bruce Herrmann.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\">{{cite web|url=http://d-45masterlist.blogspot.com/|title=Martin D-45 Master List at blogspot.com}}</ref> Instruments marked \"[E]\" are those known to exist according to either information contained herein or a separate version of the ''Martin D-45 Master List''.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\">{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/martind45masterlist/|title=Martin D-45 Master List at sites.google.com}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n!s/n!!Year!![E]!!Description\n|-\n| 53177 || 1933 || [E] || Special order for [[Gene Autry]], \"Gene Autry\" on fingerboard, 12 fret model with slotted head and \"torch\" inlay on headstock, currently in the Autry National Center in Los Angeles; photographs and other information available here.<ref name=\"autrycollections\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autrycollections.org/mwebcgi/mweb.exe?request=record;id=M510017;type=101 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217050616/http://www.autrycollections.org/mwebcgi/mweb.exe?request=record%3Bid%3DM510017%3Btype%3D101 |archive-date=2015-02-17 |url-status=dead |title=guitar |accessdate=2015-09-06 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 56394 || 1934 || [E] || Made for Jackie \"Kid\" Moore, 12 fret model with solid headstock featuring \"torch\" inlay. Presently in Hank Risan's Museum of Modern Instruments (MOMI) collection.<ref name=\"themomi.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/Dreadnoughts/1934JackieKidMooreMartinD-45.html|title=TheMoMI.org -- The Museum of Musical Instruments -- The Hank Risan Collection|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Featured in \"Acoustic Guitar\" \"Great Acoustics\" section, December 1999.<ref name=\"themomi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/articles/singingcowboys/images/2.jpg|title=Image: 2.jpg, (254 \u00d7 280 px)|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 63715 || 1936 || [E] || First 14 fret model (14 frets clear of the body), special wide body (16 1/4 Inches). On loan to, and on display at, the Martin Museum in Nazareth from collector Sten Juhlas according to.<ref name=\"yuku\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/D45-how-many-are-known-to-remain-today?page=3|title=D-45 - how many are known to remain today? in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref><ref name=\"premierguitar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/articles/20677-pre-war-perfection-the-martin-d-45?page=3|title=Pre-War Perfection: The Martin D-45 &#124; Premier Guitar|publisher=premierguitar.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> Shown in this video<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O4-I_Alw8fQ Martin D-45S 1936 Authentic Acoustic Guitar]</ref> from the Martin Museum.\n|-\n| 64890 || 1936 || [E] || D-45S Special wide body (16 1/4 Inches). Illustrated on p.&nbsp;207 of Arlen Roth, \"Complete Acoustic Guitar\", 1985 (photo provided by Gruhn Guitars, Nashville),<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Arlen Roth Complete Acoustic Guitar|author=Roth, A.|publisher=Music Sales Group|isbn=9780857127525|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1OhZc9UClmIC&pg=PA207|page=207|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> also on p.&nbsp;263 of the hardcover version of George Gruhn/Walter Carter book \"Acoustic Guitars and Other Fretted Instruments\" where it is credited to \"Steve Shaw\", therefore potentially included in the collection of the late Steven Kern Shaw (refer \"Miscellaneous\" section).\n|-\n| 65265 || 1937 || &nbsp; || 2 pick guards according to the ''D-45 master list''; current existence not known\n|-\n| 67460 || 1937 || [E] || Third and last 12 fret model, all remainder are 14 frets; the only 12 fret instrument with solid (non slotted) head and vertical \"C F Martin\" inlay as per 14-fret models. Made for Harold A. Wagler, initials \"HAW\" in fingerboard. Illustrated on p.&nbsp;248 of<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Evans, Tom & Mary Anne, \"Guitars from the Renaissance to Rock\", Paddington Press, 1977</ref> and on page 263 of the hardcover version of George Gruhn/Walter Carter book \"Acoustic Guitars and Other Fretted Instruments\". Additional background information and photos of this guitar available here.<ref name=\"yuku2\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/55397/Re-Martin-guitar-registry|title=Martin guitar registry? in The Vintage Corner Archives Volume III Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 70592 || 1938 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> ||\n|-\n| 70593 || 1938 || [E] ||  Illustrated in the \"Martin Guitar Book\", also \"The Vintage Guitar Vol. 3\"\n|-\n| 70594 || 1938 || \n|-\n| 71039 || 1938 || [E] || Previously owned by [[Red Smiley]], now in the collection of Mac Yasuda,<ref>https://www.facebook.com/groups/615182848602758/</ref> illustrations (from Japanese magazine) here.<ref name=\"chiefnoda.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chiefnoda.com/pict/pwd45/index.html|title=Pre-war D-45's|publisher=chiefnoda.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> This instrument has ornamental rhinestones inserted into the head, snowflake inlays have been replaced by more \"modern\" hexagons (engraved \"RED\" and \"D-45\" at the 12th and 19th frets, respectively), also the original D-45 back has been replaced by a later D-28 back at some point. Now in the collection of Mac Yasuda. Illustrated in his book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\".\n|-\n| 71040 || 1938 || [E] || Owned at some point by [[David Bromberg]], many repaired cracks in top, illustrated here.<ref name=\"facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MartinD45/photos/a.404929629526018.101467.403591896326458/888052011213775/?type=1|title=Martin D-45 - Timeline Photos &#124; Facebook|publisher=facebook.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> At some time in Japan, illustrations (from Japanese magazine) here.<ref name=\"chiefnoda.com\"/> For sale at Gruhn in 2009 for $110,000 (inventory no. AA7972), additional discussion here.<ref name=\"yuku3\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/81081/1938-D45-at-Gruhn|title=1938 D-45 at Gruhn in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>  Illustrated in his book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\n|-\n| 71041 || 1938 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page.,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/D45-how-many-are-known-to-remain-today?page=4|title=Martin D-45 Master List|work=martind45howmanyp4}}</ref> having been repaired in his workshop. It is cited as having forward-X bracing, snowflake inlay and being in excellent condition.\n|-\n| 71663 || 1938 || [E] || Special order with unique (?, for a D-45) sunburst top, tortoiseshell headstock veneer, F-9 (archtop) style hexagon fingerboard inlays (the latter later adopted as standard on D-45s from 1939 onwards) and additional white stripes on edges of fingerboard (also as per F-9 archtop). The \"Teeter Guitar\", owned at one time by noted repairman Don Teeter and illustrated on the cover his 1980 book \"Acoustic Guitar: Adjustment, Care, Maintenance and Repair Volume II\",<ref name=\"amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Acoustic-Guitar-Adjustment-Maintenance-Repair/dp/0806116072/|title=Acoustic Guitar: Adjustment, Care, Maintenance and Repair Volume II (2): Don E. Teeter: 9780806116075: Amazon.com: Books|publisher=amazon.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> also featured on the cover of \"Frets\" magazine, May 1988 and in the \"Encore\" section of \"Guitar Player\" magazine, February 1992<ref name=\"themomi2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themomi.org/museum/articles/Dreadnoughts/images/Feb_1992_GP.jpg|title=Image: Feb_1992_GP.jpg, (254 \u00d7 280 px)|publisher=themomi.org|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> and as a foldout on page 49 of the 1st edition of Walter Carter's Martin book. Sold by Lark Street Music in 1987 for $18,000 according to this interview with Buzzy Levine;<ref name=\"blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://kenlelen.blogspot.com.au/2010_07_01_archive.html|title=Vintage Music Concerts: July 2010|publisher=kenlelen.blogspot.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> presently in Hank Risan's Museum of Modern Instruments (MOMI) collection.<ref name=\"themomi.org\"/> Some additional discussion of this instrument here<ref name=\"yuku4\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/1595/Teeter-D45|title=Teeter D-45 in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 71664 || 1938 || [E] || Apparently was in Japan, illustrated on pp.&nbsp;23\u201324 of the (Japanese) \"Martin Vintage Guitar Guide\",<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Martin-Vintage-Guitar-Guide-VA/dp/4779619068|title=Martin Vintage Guitar Guide: 2013. editor: To\u00cc&quot;kyo\u00cc&quot; : San&#39;eishobo\u00cc&quot;: 9784779619069: Amazon.com: Books|publisher=amazon.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> pages also reproduced here<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> Now in US.\n|-\n| 71665 || 1938 || [E] || \"Possibly the last D-45 with snowflake inlays in fretboard\", illustrated here.<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/>  illustrated in \"The Vintage Guitar Vol. 3\"\n|-\n| 72160 || 1939 || [E] || Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> formerly owned by Jim Rickard.<ref name=\"jim_rickard\">{{cite web|url=http://ovationfanclub.com/megabbs/forums/thread-view.asp?tid=15628&start=1&posts=6|title=Jim Rickard's former Martin D-45|publisher=ovationfanclub.com|accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref> This instrument was used by [[Tony Rice]] on one track \"I Don\u2019t Want Your Mandolins Mister\" of his 1994 duet CD \"[[Tone Poems (Dave Grisman and Tony Rice album)|Tone Poems]]\" with [[David Grisman]], and is illustrated on the cover of \"Acoustic Guitar\" magazine, January 1996, reproduced here.<ref name=\"steve_acoustic_guitar_magazine\">{{cite web|url=http://musicmansteve.com/Maghome/AcousticGuitar.htm|title=ACOUSTIC GUITAR Magazine Backissues|publisher=musicmansteve.com|accessdate=2016-03-01}}</ref> Most recently in the collection of the late Steven Kern Shaw, now on display in the collection of instruments bequeathed by him to Belmont University<ref name=\"belmont_news\" />, as described and illustrated in this forum post.<ref name=\"umgf_t202346\">{{cite web|url=https://umgf.com/1939-d-45-s-n-72160-has-been-located-t202370.html|title=1939 D-45 , S/N 72160 , has been located|publisher=umgf.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72161 || 1939\n|-\n| 72162 || 1939\n|-\n| 72460 || 1939 || [E] || D-45S. The 'S' was for a 'special neck' which was narrower than 1 11/16\". Known to exist, cited in a post by John Arnold in this web page,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> having been for sale at Gruhn around 1990, said to be on consignment for Wilma Lee Cooper, was in somewhat poor condition. Now restored by TJ Thompson after 8 years. Formerly in the collection Mac Yasuda; llustrated his book \"Rhinestones and Twanging Tones\". Listed for sale at Carter Vintage Guitars, Nashville, as at March 2020, asking price $145,000.<ref name=\"cartervintage-72460\">{{cite web|url=https://cartervintage.com/products/martin-d-45-1939|title=Martin D-45S 1939 Product Code: GF3989}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72740 || 1939 || [E] || Known to exist, repaired by Martin during the period 1966-2001 according to this blog post.<ref name=\"martind45-repairs-1966-2001\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/180739/The-91-Pre-War-D45s|title=The 91 Pre War D-45s}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72741 || 1939 || [E] || \"Mother Maybelle\", owned by [[Stephen Stills]];<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> some additional information here<ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=Clapton's Guitar: Watching Wayne Henderson Build the Perfect Instrument|author=St. John, A.|date=2005|publisher=Free Press|isbn=9780743281980|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Eql1iLRGyAC&pg=PA33|page=33|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 72742 || 1939\n|-\n| 73126 || 1939\n|-\n| 73127 || 1939 || [E]<ref name=\"martind45masterlist2\"/> ||\n|-\n| 73128 || 1939 || [E] || Owned at one time by [[Johnny Smith]].<ref name=\"martind45masterlist\"/> Seen at Gruhn Guitars, January 2013;<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp4\"/> advertised for sale by Steve Swan Guitars, February 2015,<ref name=\"steveswanguitars\">{{cite web|url=http://www.steveswanguitars.com/items/vintage-martin-dreadnought/1939-martin-d-45/|title=1939 Martin D-45 - Steve Swan Guitars|publisher=steveswanguitars.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> for $150,000, since removed from sale; additional picture here<ref name=\"theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com\">{{cite web|url=http://theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com/topic/141870/master/1/?page=3|title=D-45 - how many are known to remain today? in The Vintage Corner Forum|publisher=theunofficialmartinguitarforum.yuku.com|accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| 73129 || 1939 || [E] || Mentioned and illustrated in this thread,<ref name=\"martind45howmanyp5\"/> for sale via Gruhn Guitars in 2012, asking price $185,000 (inventory no. AA8729). Purchased by Jim Irsay, CEO/Owner of the Indianapolis Colts.<ref name=\"indystar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/music/2013/12/04/life-by-the-strings/3872185/|title=It's life by the strings for Jim Irsay's guitar man|